description: A tri-aryl ester comprising a central 4-hydroxybenzoic acid moiety esterified with a 4-nitrobenzoic acid derivative at one end and a 2-propoxy-4-methoxybenzoic acid derivative at the other. The molecule features a linear core of three benzene rings linked by ester groups, with a terminal nitro group, a lateral propoxy chain at the 2-position of the first ring, and a methoxy substituent at the 4-position of that same ring.

A cyclolinear polyorganocarbosiloxane polymer consisting of repeating decamethyl-5-carbacyclohexasiloxane rings connected by oxygen atoms. Within each cyclic repeating unit, one oxygen atom of the siloxane ring structure is substituted with a methylene group, forming a carbosilane linkage.
A star-shaped heteroaromatic system featuring a tristriazolotriazine core substituted with three 3,4-dihexyloxyphenyl groups.
A terthiophene-based semiconducting polymer substituted with dodecyl side groups, characterized by a rigid conjugated main chain.

A quaternary ammonium salt functionalized with a trimethoxysilyl group, serving as a co-structure-directing agent to facilitate electrostatic interactions between anionic surfactants and silica precursors.

(S, S)-4 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Distinct ring compositions and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A pi-shaped polyphilic block molecule featuring a p-terphenyl core with two lateral nonyloxy chains at the 2' and 3' positions and polar glycerol units at the 4 and 4'' positions.
An aromatic aldehyde comprising a furan ring with a formyl group. It is obtained from the acid hydrolysis of pentosan-rich biomass and serves as a solvent and chemical intermediate.
A derivative of the B12 molecule in which the hydrophilic headgroups are expanded by tri(ethylene oxide) spacers.
A benzenetriol isomer with three adjacent hydroxyl groups.

phase_transition_behavior: No clearing point (T_NI/T_Iso) is reported in the provided tables or figure captions for C16-IKPEAP; no thermotropic phase-transition sequence is given from which a clearing point could be inferred.
description: C16-IKPEAP is an N-acylated hexapeptide in which a linear C16 alkyl chain (palmitoyl group) is attached through an amide bond to the N-terminus of the peptide sequence Ile–Lys–Pro–Glu–Ala–Pro. The backbone consists of repeating amide (peptide) linkages between the six amino-acid residues. The two proline residues each contribute a five-membered pyrrolidine ring that is incorporated into the peptide backbone nitrogen. The lysine residue bears a terminal primary amine on a (CH2)4 side chain, and the glutamic acid residue bears a terminal carboxylic acid on a (CH2)2 side chain; the C-terminus is a carboxylic acid on the final proline residue. The compound was prepared by stepwise solid-phase peptide synthesis of the IKPEAP sequence followed by N-terminal acylation with a palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl) group, then global deprotection and cleavage to give the isolated peptide as a salt.
A heterocyclic ester compound featuring a 5-ethoxyfuran-2-carboxylate group linked to a 4-nitrophenyl 4-oxybenzoate scaffold. The molecule contains a furan ring substituted with an ethoxy group.

A cyclotriphosphazene-based star molecule featuring a central inorganic ring substituted with six dodecyloxy-terminated aromatic side chains. The molecular architecture consists of a hexasubstituted cyclotriphosphazene core linked to six 4-((4-((4-dodecyloxybenzylidene)amino)phenyl)iminomethyl)phenoxy groups, incorporating rigid aromatic segments, flexible long alkyl tails, and polarizable azomethine linkages.

An unsaturated wax ester formed from the condensation of two C18 hydrocarbon chains, each containing a cis-double bond at the ninth carbon. The molecule features a central ester linkage flanked by two alkenyl tails.
A cationic poly(4-vinylpyridine) derivative with tetradecyl side chains and a counterion denoted as In-. It forms ordered hexagonal structures after annealing in a humid atmosphere.

Rotor 14 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A side-chain polymer synthesized via atom transfer radical polymerization, featuring a repeating unit with a methacrylate backbone. This backbone is connected by a butyl spacer to a core structure composed of two phenyl rings linked by an ester group, ending in a terminal methoxy group.

A rod-like fluorinated molecule comprising a para-nitrophenyl group connected to a pentafluorophenyl ring by a tetrafluoroethylene unit. Obtained via reaction of a fluoroalkylcopper species with 1-iodo-4-nitrobenzene.

A bis-azo derivative containing two amino electron-donating groups, one on a terminal phenyl ring and one on a terminal naphthalene ring, connected by a central phenyl spacer. This donor-pi-donor architecture is designed for high two-photon absorption cross-sections.

description: A dicationic salt consisting of two N-undecylimidazolium rings linked at the nitrogen positions by an ethylene bridge, balanced by two tetrafluoroborate anions.
The S-enantiomer of an aromatic alpha-hydroxy acid utilized in chiral synthesis.

NPG-d4 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Terminal groups and ring variations modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A star-shaped organic molecule comprising a central benzene core substituted with five phenylethynyl arms. Four of these arms are terminated with pentyloxy groups, while the fifth arm is connected via an undecyloxy spacer to an (R)-lipoic acid ester moiety containing a dithiolane ring.

A benzodifuran-based molecule with a T-shaped architecture, comprising a central core flanked by butyl ester groups and a 4-nitrophenyl substituent. It is prepared by condensing a diamino-benzodifuran precursor with 3-methoxybenzaldehyde. The molecule features two imine linkages and methoxy groups, functioning as a yellow emitter in the solid state, though lacking the intramolecular hydrogen bonding found in its hydroxy-analog.
Rod-like nanoparticles composed of linear polymer chains of beta-1,4-linked D-glucose units organized into crystalline domains, featuring surface sulfate ester groups.
A p-terphenyl core substituted with two lateral hexyloxy chains at the 2' and 3' positions and polar glycerol units at the 4 and 4'' positions.
A six-membered cyclic carbonate monomer substituted with a methyl group and an ethyl ester group, synthesized via cyclization of a diol intermediate.

An organic molecule featuring an ethyl 2,3,5,6-tetrafluorobenzoate core connected via an ethynyl linker to a phenyl ring substituted with a 7,7,8,8,9,9,10,10,11,11,12,12,13,13,14,14,14-heptadecafluorotetradecyloxy chain.
A tri-acetylated ribonucleoside synthesized from guanosine and acetic anhydride. It serves as a protected intermediate in the synthesis of modified nucleosides.

A short peptide derivative synthesized by the condensation of Z-GlyGly-OSu with ethanolamine, followed by deprotection and acetylation using acetyl chloride. It features a diglycine backbone capped with an acetyl group at the N-terminus and a 2-hydroxyethyl group at the C-terminus amide.

A gold(III) pincer complex featuring a 2,6-bis(3,4-bis(dodecyloxy)phenyl)pyridine ligand coordinated to the metal center, with a 3,4-bis(1H,1H,2H,2H-perfluorooctyloxy)phenylacetylide ligand occupying the fourth coordination site.
A hexaglycerol backbone esterified with a single dodecanoic acid chain.

The compound is a chiral poly(thiophene) derivative, specifically identified as PBMBT, which consists of a poly(3,4-di((S)-2-methylbutoxy)thiophene) structure featuring (S)-2-methylbutoxy side chains attached to the thiophene backbone.

Produced by the condensation of 1,4-phenylenediamine with cinnamaldehyde. The molecule is symmetric, featuring a central 1,4-phenylene diamine core linked to two 3-phenylallylidene groups via imine bonds.
Prepared from 1,12-dodecanediamine and tridecanedioic acid, this aliphatic polymer contains long hydrophobic methylene sequences interrupted by amide bonds.
The molecule features a rigid biphenyl core structure that is terminated at both the 4 and 4' positions with glycidyl ether functional groups.
A silylated benzonitrile derivative where the hydroxyl group is protected with a tert-butyldimethylsilyl group. It functions as an AB-type monomer for the chain-growth synthesis of polysulfates.

The substance is a supramolecular complex resulting from the coordination of potassium iodide to the crown ether moiety of a dodecyl-substituted L-DOPA hybrid. Within this structure, the potassium ion is complexed by the crown ether ring.

A sulfur-containing homopolymer derived from phenoxy propylene sulfide using anionic ring-opening polymerization. This amorphous material exhibits a glass formation event near ambient conditions, reflecting the properties of its aromatic side chains. It serves as a macroinitiator for block copolymer synthesis.
Intermediate 9. Colorless oil.
A furan derivative containing a carboxylic acid group at the 2-position. It is produced by the oxidation of furfural and appears as a metabolite in degradation pathways.

This compound is an alkylated biphenyl carbonitrile. It is synthesized by the etherification of 4'-hydroxy-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-carbonitrile with 1,6-dibromohexane. The molecule consists of a biphenyl backbone substituted with a cyano group and an ether-linked alkyl chain.

description: A dicationic bis-imidazolium salt in which two imidazolium rings are linked at the nitrogen atoms by an ethylene bridge, while the remaining nitrogen atom on each ring is substituted with a dodecyl aliphatic chain. The counterions are tetrafluoroborate.
An aromatic isomer with amino and nitro substituents in the meta position, utilized for its acentric crystalline arrangement.

A tetrasilylated macrocycle featuring a 14-membered tetraaza ring where each nitrogen is connected to a 3-(triethoxysilyl)propyl group. This organosilane is employed as a building block in co-condensation reactions to introduce metal-ion chelating functionalities into silica materials.

A star-shaped organic molecule with C3 symmetry, featuring a central benzene-1,3,5-tricarboxamide unit linked to three oligo(p-phenylenevinylene) arms. Each arm ends in a 3,4-bis(dodecyloxy)phenyl moiety. It is synthesized to explore the effect of alkoxy chain position and is known to act as an organogelator in nonpolar solvents like toluene and decane.
A block copolymer comprising a hydrophilic polyether block and a hydrophobic polycarbonate block with pendant ethyl ester groups, prepared via ring-opening polymerization.

The compound is a supramolecular complex based on a hexadecyl-substituted L-DOPA hybrid. It features a crown ether moiety to which sodium iodide is coordinated. The structure represents a host-guest assembly involving the functionalized amino acid and the sodium salt.

description: The molecule is constructed around a linear pentathiophene backbone, consisting of five thiophene rings connected via carbon–carbon single bonds at their alpha positions. Both terminal thiophene rings are substituted with n-hexyl chains. The central thiophene ring features a side chain attached via a methylene spacer (–CH2–), which connects to an oligo(ethylene oxide) segment containing approximately ten –CH2–CH2–O– repeat units, terminated by an alkyl or alkoxy group.

A bis-ligand iron(II) complex consisting of an iron(II) center coordinated by two 2,6-bis((tetradecylimino)methyl)pyridine ligands, balanced by tetrafluoroborate anions. The coordination core is surrounded by peripheral tetradecyl alkyl chains.

An ester derivative comprising a central 1-acetyl-4,5-dihydro-1H-pyrazole ring, a 4-(octyloxy)phenyl group, and an azobenzene unit attached to a 4-(decyloxy)benzoate chain. Prepared by esterification of a phenolic azo-pyrazole.
A bicyclic organic compound derived from camphor. It features a benzylidene group with a methyl substituent and serves as a UVB filter.

A rod-like organic nanomaterial consisting of rigid, linear chains of beta-1,4-linked D-glucose units packed into a highly crystalline, needle-shaped lattice. The surface features negatively charged sulfate ester groups.
A diamino-substituted nitrobenzene derivative designed as a push-pull molecule to enhance second harmonic generation efficiency.
An absorbable polyester homopolymer consisting of 4-hydroxybutyrate units.
A rigid, fused polycyclic heteroaromatic system extending the carbazole structure with additional benzo-fusion, used for its luminescent properties.
A biodegradable polyester produced by bacteria, consisting of 3-hydroxybutyrate units.

c-DOPA(12) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A linear oligomer formed by the aza-Michael addition of n-butylamine to a diacrylate monomer. The repeating unit consists of a central 2-methyl-1,4-phenylene bis(4-oxybenzoate) core connected to hexyl spacers, which are linked via tertiary amine junctions derived from the n-butylamine addition to the acrylate groups.
A radical photoinitiator featuring a phenyl ketone moiety substituted at the alpha carbon with two methyl groups and a 2-hydroxyethoxy chain. Used to initiate polymerization upon UV exposure.
A star-shaped compound featuring a tristriazolotriazine scaffold substituted with three 4-(2-octyldecyloxy)phenyl groups.
A piperidinopyrimidine derivative featuring an N-oxide group. Chemically, it functions as a potassium channel opener and is used for its vasodilatory properties.

Huang-C5 is an aromatic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It includes heteroatoms and extended conjugation, while ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A salt comprising a five-membered diaza-heterocyclic cation and a methyl-substituted sulfonate anion. It is investigated for thermal energy storage capabilities due to its high enthalpy of fusion.
An anthranilate ester formed from menthol. It provides protection against UVA radiation in sunscreen formulations.
A disk-like aromatic compound comprising a tristriazolotriazine core substituted with three 3,4-dipentyloxyphenyl groups.

A glycosteroid derivative in which a disaccharide headgroup is linked to a cholesterol unit via a butyl-acetamide spacer, and features a tetradecyl carbamate chain attached laterally to the sugar moiety.
A steroid ester resulting from the formal condensation of the 3-hydroxy group of cholesterol with the carboxy group of 24-methylpentacosanoic acid.
A diaryl sulfone derivative featuring one hydroxyl group and one fluorosulfonyloxy group. It is a solid intermediate synthesized for the production of sulfone-containing polysulfates.
A metal-organic precursor consisting of a zirconium center coordinated to four dimethylamido groups, utilized in vapor deposition processes for dielectric films.
A planar nitrogen-rich heterocycle consisting of a heptazine core with three amino substituents, forming parallel layers in the solid state and acting as an intermediate to graphitic carbon nitride.
A conjugated organic molecule featuring a central 9H-carbazole moiety substituted with phenyl rings at the 3 and 6 positions, serving as a blue-emitting chromophore.

An intermediate alcohol synthesized via Williamson etherification of a fluorophenyl-pyrimidine phenol with 10-bromo-1-decanol. It features a rigid pyrimidine-based aromatic core substituted with a dodecyloxy tail and a hydroxyl-terminated decyl chain.

An organic semiconductor comprising a central benzene core decorated with two ether-linked 3,4,5-tris(dodecyloxy)benzyl dendrons and two 2-(4-pyridyl)vinyl arms. The terminal pyridine rings serve as hydrogen bond acceptors. This fluorescent dye is structurally related to phenyleneethynylene derivatives but contains vinylene linkages in the conjugated backbone.

A guanidinium-sulfonimide salt comprising an N-(4-(dodecyloxy)phenyl)-N',N',N'',N''-tetramethylguanidinium cation and a ((4-(dodecyloxy)phenyl)sulfonyl)(methylsulfonyl)amide anion, synthesized via anion exchange.
An oligophenylenevinylene analogue consisting of a central benzene and two outer phenyl rings substituted with long branched 2-decyltetradecyl groups, existing as a fluid at room temperature.
A linear conjugated oligomer consisting of four phenyl rings connected in a para-arrangement with a cyano terminus.
Compound 19[ClO4] is identified as 1,3-didodecylimidazolium perchlorate, which features an imidazolium core substituted with two long dodecyl alkyl side chains.
A fluorinated derivative of RM734 with a fluorine atom at the 3-position of the central ring. The increased dipole moment leads to a large spontaneous polarisation.

description: The molecule is a 3,5-disubstituted 1,2,4-oxadiazole derivative linking two distinct aromatic systems. The central 1,2,4-oxadiazole ring is substituted at the 3-position by a para-phenylene ring which is further substituted with a benzyloxycarbonyl group (a benzyl ester of benzoic acid). At the 5-position, the oxadiazole is attached to a biphenyl unit (specifically, a 4,4'-biphenyl system). The distal phenyl ring of this biphenyl moiety is substituted at the para position with an ester linkage connecting to a chiral aliphatic chain. Specifically, this ester linkage consists of a carbonyl group attached to the biphenyl ring, bonded to an oxygen atom that is part of a 3-(nonyloxy)-2-methyl-3-oxopropyl chain. This terminal fragment contains a stereogenic center at the 2-position (a methyl group) and terminates in a nonyl ester.
A heptazine derivative substituted with three 4-fluoro-2-methylphenyl moieties, used as an electron acceptor to form exciplexes in light-emitting diodes.

A donor-acceptor tolane molecule comprising a tetrafluorobenzonitrile acceptor and an electron-rich phenyl ring substituted with a tridecafluorodecyloxy chain. Prepared by nucleophilic substitution on pentafluorobenzonitrile.

A C3-symmetrical molecule constructed from a benzene-1,3,5-tricarboxamide core and three oligo(p-phenylenevinylene) branches. The terminal groups are 3,5-bis(dodecyloxy)phenyl rings. This structural variation is synthesized to study self-assembly behaviors but fails to form ordered supramolecular structures or gels.

Bn12 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A saturated medium-chain fatty acid consisting of a twelve-carbon aliphatic tail terminating in a carboxylic acid group. It is commonly found in coconut oil.

A Janus amphiphile comprising a hydrophobic cholest-5-en-3-yl unit linked to a hydrophilic disaccharide head group through a flexible butyl-acetamide spacer, representing the core structure of the series without any lateral alkyl chains attached to the sugar moiety.
A chiral aromatic alpha-hydroxy acid with a phenolic hydroxyl group at the para position, utilized as a fine chemical precursor.

description: The molecule consists of a central 4,4′-biphenyl core substituted at both para positions. Extending from each side of this central core is an alkoxy chain containing a nonamethylene spacer (–O–(CH2)9–). These spacers are connected via thioether linkages (–S–) to terminal 4,4′-biphenyl units. Each of these outer biphenyl groups is substituted at the para position of the distal ring with a nitrile (–C≡N) functional group. The overall structure is symmetric, featuring three biphenyl fragments, two ether linkages, two nonyl alkyl chains, two thioether bonds, and two terminal cyano groups.
A synthetic naphthoic acid derivative characterized by a bulky adamantyl side chain. It is structurally designed to mimic the activity of retinoids by binding to nuclear receptors.

phase_transition_behavior: Table 1 reports for PMA4 (x = 100 mol%): TgPMA4 = 305 K; nematic-to-isotropic transition TNI = 357 K (clearing point).
description: This is a polymethacrylate in which each repeat unit consists of a carbon–carbon polymer backbone bearing an α-methyl substituent and an ester side chain. The ester oxygen is connected to a six-carbon alkyl spacer that terminates in an ether linkage to a substituted phenyl ring. This aromatic ring carries a methyl substituent and is connected through an azo linkage (–N=N–) to a second phenyl ring that is substituted with a pentyloxy group. The polymer is synthesized by polymerization of the corresponding methacrylate monomer bearing the azobenzene-containing alkoxy side chain.

A symmetric chiral diimine synthesized by the condensation of 1,3-propylenediamine and (+)-camphor in toluene using p-toluenesulfonic acid as a catalyst. The molecule features two rigid 1,7,7-trimethylbicyclo[2.2.1]heptane moieties linked by a flexible propylene chain via C=N double bonds. It is characterized by its specific optical rotation and conformational flexibility, with potential applications as a chiral dopant or biologically active agent.
A short-chain carboxylic acid consisting of a methyl group bonded to a carboxyl moiety. It readily forms cyclic dimers with two hydrogen bonds in the gaseous state.
An organic benzene derivative featuring an amino group and a nitro group at para positions, with an additional methyl substituent on the ring to induce non-centrosymmetric packing.
A dithiol compound consisting of a diethyl ether chain terminated with thiol groups. It serves as a flexible chain extender or spacer in thiol-ene reactions.

A common thermoplastic polymer produced by the polymerization of methyl methacrylate. It is characterized by a methacrylic backbone with methyl ester side groups, known for its optical transparency and rigidity.

A zwitterionic small molecule consisting of an imidazolium cation core substituted with a polymerizable 4-vinylbenzyl group and a propyl sulfonate anion. This functionalized monomer contains both a styrene-like reactive handle and internal charge separation.

A bicyclic aromatic amine consisting of a naphthalene core substituted with amino groups at the 1 and 5 positions. It is widely used as a bifunctional curing agent for epoxy resins to facilitate the formation of cross-linked polymer networks.
A supramolecular complex formed by the coordination of potassium hexafluorophosphate to the crown ether moiety of a tetradecyl-substituted tetrahydroisoquinoline hybrid.
A chiral alpha-hydroxy acid analogue of phenylalanine.
A melt-processable modified PTFE containing perfluoropropylvinylether comonomers.
A dinuclear metallosurfactant salt featuring a mu-oxo-hexachlorodiferrate(III) dianion. The organic cations form non-interdigitated bilayers, separating the inorganic magnetic units.

c-THIQ(16) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

(R, R)-1 is an aromatic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate the steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A fluorinated organic compound consisting of an ethyl 2-cyanoacrylate core substituted with a 4-trifluoromethylphenyl group. This electron-deficient monomer is prepared by condensing 4-(trifluoromethyl)benzaldehyde with ethyl cyanoacetate.

The molecule consists of a fused dibenzo[a,c]phenazine polycyclic aromatic core incorporating two nitrogen atoms within the ring system. Attached to this aromatic framework at the 2, 3, 6, and 7 positions are four hexyloxy substituents, each linked via an aryl–oxygen single bond to form peripheral –O–(CH2)5CH3 chains. At the 11-position of the core, a carboxylate group forms an ester linkage; specifically, the acyl carbonyl is bonded to an oxygen atom that connects to a linear six-carbon alkyl chain terminating in a primary hydroxyl group, resulting in a –C(=O)O–(CH2)6–OH moiety.
A phenylethanoid alcohol acting as an antioxidant.

A wholly aromatic homopolymer synthesized from 4'-acetoxybiphenyl-4-carboxylic acid. The linear polymer chain is composed exclusively of rigid 4'-oxybiphenyl-4-carbonyl repeating units linked by ester bonds, resulting in a highly thermally stable structure.

A pi-shaped polyphilic block molecule featuring a p-terphenyl core with two lateral hexadecyloxy chains at the 2' and 3' positions and polar glycerol units at the 4 and 4'' positions. Synthesized via Suzuki cross-coupling of a 1,2-bis(hexadecyloxy)-3,6-diiodobenzene intermediate with a boronic acid derivative containing a protected glycerol moiety, followed by acidic deprotection.

A glucose derivative in which the hydroxyls are acetylated and the anomeric carbon is substituted with an isothiocyanate group. This linear dipole allows for anisotropic packing but results in different solid-state properties compared to the corresponding azide.

A fatty acid derivative comprising a stearic acid backbone with a cyclic nitroxide radical moiety incorporated at the 5-position. This paramagnetic molecule is utilized as a spin probe to monitor the environment near the polar interface of molecular assemblies.
A fluorinated polyether polymer consisting of repeating units formed by an octafluoro-substituted terphenyl rigid core linked via ether bonds to flexible octamethylene spacers.

A glycoconjugate comprising a steroidal cholest-5-en-3-yl moiety linked to a disaccharide unit through a butyl-acetamide spacer. The disaccharide structure is modified at the 2-position with a lateral butyl chain attached via a carbamate linkage.
A mononuclear three-coordinate copper(I) complex coordinating two N-benzoylthiourea ligands and a bromide anion, where the ligands bear heptyloxy and perfluorooctyl substituents.

This organic molecule features a rigid aromatic core composed of two phenyl rings linked by an ester bond. One end of the core is substituted with a methoxy group, while the other connects to a flexible hexyloxy spacer terminated by a polymerizable acrylate moiety.
A nonionic surfactant molecule comprising a hydrophobic stearyl chain attached via an amide linkage to a hydrophilic, methyl-terminated octa(ethylene glycol) oligomer.
A catalyst (in molten state or vapor) used in the CVD process for the preparation of carbon nanotubes, specifically in aerogel spinning (FCCVD).

An ortho-substituted nitrobenzene derivative containing a tetrafluoroethylene bridge connecting to a pentafluorophenyl moiety. Prepared via a copper-mediated cross-coupling reaction with the corresponding aryl iodide.

The simplest aromatic carboxylic acid, featuring a phenyl group attached directly to a carboxyl functional group. It is known to exist as a hydrogen-bonded cyclic dimer in the vapor phase at lower temperatures.

4-cyano-3,5-difluorophenyl 2',3,5,6'-tetrafluoro-4'-propyl-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-carboxylate is a polyfluorinated biphenyl ester. It comprises a tetrafluorobiphenyl moiety with a propyl chain, linked via an ester group to a 3,5-difluoro-4-cyanophenyl terminal unit.

This aromatic organic scaffold features a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It exhibits extended conjugation and heteroatom-containing functional groups. Substituent patterns and terminal groups modulate steric bulk, polarity, and electronic distribution.

An aromatic ester synthesized by the condensation of 4-hexyloxybenzoic acid with hydroquinone. The molecule contains a terminal hydroxyl group and a central ester linkage connecting two benzene rings.
A p-terphenyl core substituted with two lateral tetracosyloxy chains at the 2' and 3' positions and glycerol units at the 4 and 4'' positions.

A gold(III) complex featuring a 2,6-bis(phenyl)pyridine pincer ligand substituted with four dodecyloxy chains at the 3 and 4 positions of the phenyl rings, coordinated to a phenylacetylide ligand bearing three 1H,1H,2H,2H-perfluorooctyloxy chains at the 3, 4, and 5 positions.

A naphthalene-based azo dye featuring an amino group at the 1-position and a phenyldiazenyl group at the 4-position. This donor-pi structure exhibits redshifted absorption compared to the unsubstituted analog.
A commercial aromatic diamine consisting of a fluorene core geminally substituted with two 4-aminophenyl groups. Purified by recrystallization from chloroform/hexane.
A modified ribonucleoside featuring a trifluoromethyl group on the guanine base. It is prepared by deprotection of its acetylated precursor.

A copper(II) complex in which the metal center is coordinated by the tetrapyrrole nitrogen atoms of a pyropheophorbide-a moiety, which is attached via an ester linkage to the sn-2 position of a glycerol backbone; the sn-1 position is esterified with a palmitoyl group, and the sn-3 position bears a phosphocholine headgroup.
A triazine-based organic compound commonly used in cosmetic formulations. It functions as a UVB absorber and is characterized by its high photostability and affinity for skin keratin.

4-((4-nitrophenoxy)carbonyl)phenyl 4-methoxy-2-propoxybenzoate (5a) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
