description:
Disodium N-dodecylaspartate consists of a linear dodecyl (C12) alkyl chain attached to the nitrogen of an aspartate-derived backbone, forming a secondary amine linkage (dodecyl–NH–). The nitrogen is bonded to the aspartate α-carbon, which also bears two carboxylate substituents: one directly attached carboxylate group (–C(=O)O−) and one side-chain carboxylate reached through a methylene spacer (–CH2–C(=O)O−). The molecule contains no rings or multiple bonds other than the carbonyl groups of the two carboxylates, and charge balance is provided by two sodium counterions.

As described in the experimental section, the disodium salt was synthesized following prior literature procedures. In general synthetic terms, such an N-dodecyl amino-acid surfactant can be obtained by forming the N–C bond through N-alkylation of an aspartate nitrogen using a dodecyl electrophile (e.g., a dodecyl halide or similar activated dodecyl derivative), followed by conversion/neutralization of the two carboxylic acid groups to their disodium carboxylate form.

The 2:1 co-crystal of 4-(n-pentyloxy)benzoic acid and (E)-1,2-bis(pyridin-4-yl)ethene consists of components connected by intermolecular hydrogen bonds linking the carboxylic acid groups to the pyridine nitrogen atoms, forming a linear, rod-like extended structure.
A phosphorylated furan derivative synthesized enzymatically from glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate. It serves as a key intermediate in the biosynthetic pathway of methanofuran.

DPCE-ACh features a rigid aromatic core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
Optically active monomer (TOR*) prepared from 3-methoxythiophene.

A macromolecule consisting of a polyamide-1 backbone derived from n-hexyl isocyanate units. The structure is characterized by a helical conformation induced by steric crowding of the pendant n-hexyl alkyl chains attached to the nitrogen atoms of the main chain.

An anthraquinone derivative conjugated to a carboxylic acid-terminated alkyl chain via an amine linker. It self-assembles into nanotubes in aqueous solution, which can transform into ribbons upon reduction.
A trimeric complex formed from two equivalents of an octyloxystilbazole and one equivalent of a dibromoperfluorobenzene, assembled via halogen bonding interactions.
A distyrylbenzene chromophore with extended branched 2-dodecylhexadecyl alkoxy chains at the 2,5-positions of the terminal rings, showing very low temperature thermal events.
A donor-acceptor molecule constructed from a central heptazine acceptor and three phenoxazine donor units, exhibiting deep red emission due to orbital delocalization.

phase_transition_behavior: From Table 2 for polymer IV-Et (poly(decaethylcyclohexasiloxane-2,8-ethylene)): Tg = -104 °C; Ti (isotropization/clearing) = 220 °C.
description: Poly(decaethylcyclohexasiloxane-2,8-ethylene) is a cyclolinear polymer composed of six-membered siloxane rings containing alternating silicon and oxygen atoms. In this structure, successive cyclic units are linked via two-carbon ethylene spacers (Si–CH2–CH2–Si) connected at the 2 and 8 positions of the silicon atoms on the ring. The remaining silicon atoms in each cyclic unit are substituted with ethyl groups, resulting in a total of ten ethyl groups per repeating unit: four silicon atoms carry two ethyl groups each, while the two silicon atoms at the linkage sites carry one ethyl group each. The polymer backbone is formed through the creation of Si–C bonds derived from the conversion of vinyl groups into the connecting ethylene bridges.

A pi-shaped polyphilic block molecule featuring a p-terphenyl core with two lateral tetradecyloxy chains at the 2' and 3' positions and polar glycerol units at the 4 and 4'' positions. Synthesized via Suzuki cross-coupling of a 1,2-bis(tetradecyloxy)-3,6-diiodobenzene intermediate with a boronic acid derivative containing a protected glycerol moiety, followed by acidic deprotection.

A fluorinated synthetic corticosteroid characterized by a pregnadiene core structure. It features a ketone at position 3, hydroxyl groups at positions 11, 17, and 21, and a methyl group at position 16, utilized for its potent anti-inflammatory properties.

A 1-methylimidazole-based organic semiconductor prepared by condensation chemistry. The central heteroaromatic ring bears 4-(dimethylamino)phenyl donors at the 4,5-positions and a 4-cyanophenyl acceptor at the 2-position.
A highly porous transition metal carbide material, prepared by treating a carbon template with gaseous titanium iodide to form a rigid inorganic network.

A long-chain primary aliphatic amine consisting of a saturated linear eighteen-carbon alkyl group attached to a terminal amino moiety. It is frequently employed as a cationic surfactant to modify the surface charge of colloidal particles and films.

phase_transition_behavior: 3D crystal → intermediate ordered phase → isotropic liquid (for the n = 10 derivative an intermediate nematic-like phase is indicated before the isotropic state).
description: The molecule features an azobenzene core composed of two benzene rings linked by a central azo group (–N=N–). Both aromatic rings are substituted at the para positions with decyloxy groups (–O–(CH2)9–CH3), resulting in two extended linear alkyl ether chains. Additionally, one of the benzene rings contains a methyl group at the meta position relative to the azo linkage, creating an unsymmetrical substitution pattern on the 4,4′-dialkoxyazobenzene framework. The synthesis involves introducing the decyloxy chains via ether formation on phenolic precursors, followed by the assembly of the azo linkage between the substituted aromatic fragments to yield the final unsymmetrically substituted structure.
A partial ester synthesized from diglycerol and dodecanoic acid, characterized by a hydrophilic ether-diol headgroup and a hydrophobic alkyl tail.
A sodium salt of a saturated twelve-carbon fatty acid. It forms hydrated crystals that dissolve into micelles at the Krafft temperature, exhibiting a characteristic solubility boundary.

A synthesized molecule containing a 1-acetyl-4,5-dihydro-1H-pyrazole heterocycle, a 4-butoxyphenyl group, and an azobenzene unit linked to a 4-(tetradecyloxy)benzoate ester. Synthesized via reaction of a pyrazolyl-phenol with an acyl chloride.
A semi-aromatic polyamide derived from hexamethylenediamine and terephthalic acid.
A secondary amine consisting of two propyl groups attached to a central nitrogen atom. It acts as a base catalyst in the thiol-Michael addition reaction.

A chiral organic molecule comprising an adenine unit connected to a triphenylamine core through a branched (R)-2-methylpropyl linker, wherein the triphenylamine scaffold is substituted with two dodecyloxy chains.

An aromatic copolyester synthesized from 2,5-diethoxyterephthalic acid and hydroquinone in a 1:1 molar ratio. The polymer backbone consists of alternating 1,4-phenylene rings and 2,5-diethoxy-substituted terephthalate units connected by ester linkages.

A peracetylated galactose derivative bearing a beta-azide functional group. The molecule features an axial acetyl group at the C4 position, a structural variation that affects its packing into solid-state assemblies.
A molecule characterized by a central 3-methoxyphenyl ring with a lateral methoxy group, connecting a 4-hexyloxyphenyl imine arm and a 4-fluorobenzoate ester arm.
A crosslinking monomer consisting of a polyethylene glycol chain terminated at both ends with acrylate ester groups.

An asymmetric bolaamphiphile consisting of a beta-D-glucopyranosyl headgroup and a diglycine-ethanolamine tail linked by a linear C20 aliphatic spacer. The structure features an eicosanediamide core, where one amide nitrogen is substituted with the glucose moiety and the other is attached to a glycylglycyl-N-(2-hydroxyethyl)amide chain.

A complex comprising a dodecyl-substituted viologen zwitterion, specifically 3-(1'-dodecyl-4,4'-bipyridinium-1-yl)propane-1-sulfonate, combined with the organic imide acid bis(trifluoromethane)sulfonimide.
An aliphatic polyamide synthesized from 11-aminoundecanoic acid, often derived from castor oil.
A stilbenoid phytoalexin with a trans-stilbene backbone and two hydroxyl groups.
A phenylethanoid with a catechol ring structure.

c-DOPA(16) • KSCN is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A solid lipid-like surfactant comprising a hexaglycerol backbone and a stearyl chain, used in dermato-cosmetic emulsions.
An imidazolium chloride salt substituted at the 1- and 3-positions with decyl and methyl groups, respectively.

A mixed-halide iron complex salt containing the mu-oxo-trichlorotribromodiferrate(III) dianion. Synthesized from dodecylpyridinium chloride and iron(II) bromide, it adopts a layered structure with antiferromagnetic coupling between iron centers.

RM230 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate the steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A fluorine-substituted diester molecule formed by the reaction of 4-fluoro-2-methoxybenzoic acid with a 4-nitrophenyl 4-hydroxybenzoate intermediate. It features a fluoro substituent on the terminal anisole ring.
A hexaglycerol ester of palmitic acid, employed as a lipid-based excipient for filament-based printing.
An acyclic acetal formed from the reaction of formaldehyde equivalents with ethanol. It is a colorless liquid characterized by two ethoxy groups attached to a central methylene carbon.

A pyrrole derivative substituted with a p-chlorophenyl group, a trifluoromethyl group, a bromine atom, and a carbonitrile group. It features an ethoxymethyl group attached to the pyrrole nitrogen atom.

phase_transition_behavior: n = 4 (CBS4OBO4SCB): Heating: Cr 235.3 N 253.2 I. Cooling: I 249.5 N 196.6 Cr. (No monotropic SmA/NTB listed for n = 4.)
description: The molecule is a symmetric trimer centered on a 4,4′-biphenyl core. Attached to the para positions of this central core are two identical substituents, each consisting of a butoxy spacer group (–O–(CH2)4–). These spacers terminate in a thioether linkage (–S–) which connects to an outer cyanobiphenyl unit. Specifically, the sulfur atom is bonded to the para position of one ring of the terminal biphenyl fragment, while the para position of the outermost ring bears a nitrile group (–C≡N). The overall structure can be described as two 4-(4-cyanobiphenyl-4′-ylthio)butoxy arms extending from the 4 and 4′ positions of a central biphenyl moiety.
A phosphatidylcholine in which the glycerol backbone is esterified at the sn-1 position by a saturated palmitoyl chain and at the sn-2 position by an unsaturated oleoyl chain.
A biodegradable aliphatic polymer formed by the polycondensation of 1,4-butanediol and adipic acid, consisting of methylene sequences linked by ester bonds.

An organic ester characterized by a 4-tert-butylphenyl group linked to a 2-cyano-2-propenoate framework. The bulky tert-butyl group at the para position influences the steric properties of this monomer synthesized from 4-tert-butylbenzaldehyde.

A reactive organic polymer prepared from 3-(triethoxysilyl)propyl isocyanate using a titanium-based catalyst. Unlike its alkyl analogs, the presence of bulky triethoxysilyl side groups prevents the formation of a helical backbone, resulting in a flexible, random-coil configuration containing hydrolyzable alkoxysilyl moieties for cross-linking.
A fluorinated tolane ethyl ester featuring a tridecafluorododecyloxy flexible chain.
An N-acyl-L-alanine derivative in which the acyl group is specified as myristoyl.

phase_transition_behavior: Cryst. → SmA → Iso. on heating; Iso. → SmA → SmC* → Cryst. on cooling (tilted phase observed only on cooling).
description: The molecule is built around a central 1,2,4-oxadiazole ring substituted at the 3- and 5-positions. The 3-position is attached to a para-phenylene group which forms part of a benzoate ester; specifically, this is a 4-(dodecyloxycarbonyl)phenyl moiety. The 5-position of the oxadiazole is linked to a biphenyl unit. The distal ring of this biphenyl system is substituted at the para-position with a carbonate-linked chiral alkyl chain. This terminal fragment consists of a 1-(octyloxycarbonyl)ethyl carbonate group, containing a stereogenic center at the carbon atom adjacent to the carbonate oxygen. The overall structure comprises a linear dodecyl chain at one end, a central core featuring a 1,2,4-oxadiazole and a biphenyl system, and a branched, chiral octyl ester terminus at the other.
A cyclolinear polymer with hexaethylcyclotetrasiloxane units connected by ethylene spacers. The backbone alternates between siloxane rings and hydrocarbon linkers.

A zinc-based zeolitic imidazolate framework with a cag topology, composed of zinc ions coordinated by imidazolate linkers. It exhibits a complex thermal behavior involving amorphization and recrystallization prior to melting.
A star-shaped compound featuring a tris([1,2,4]triazolo)[1,5-a:1',5'-c:1'',5''-e][1,3,5]triazine central core substituted at the 2, 5, and 9 positions with three 3,4-dihexadecyloxyphenyl groups.

An anionic phospholipid consisting of a glycerol moiety linked via a phosphodiester bond to the sn-3 position of a diacylglycerol backbone, which is esterified with a palmitoyl chain at the sn-1 position and an oleoyl chain at the sn-2 position.

(S, S)-7 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A rod-like aromatic ester comprising a 4-nitrophenyl ester moiety linked to a central phenyl ring, which is in turn esterified with a 2-nonyloxy-4-methoxybenzoyl group.
An aliphatic polyamide synthesized from tetramethylenediamine and adipic acid, exhibiting high thermal resistance.

An ethyl ester derivative of 2-cyano-3-phenyl-2-propenoic acid featuring a methyl substituent at the ortho position of the phenyl ring. It is prepared by the condensation of 2-methylbenzaldehyde with ethyl cyanoacetate in the presence of piperidine.
Nanometric rods composed of a cellulose II polymorph backbone, modified via esterification with acetyl groups to a degree of substitution of 1.14.
A nonionic surfactant molecule comprising an alpha-D-xyloside sugar head group connected to a decyl alkyl chain via a diethylene glycol (dioxyethyl) linker.

RM734-F2 (X=Y=F) comprises a rigid aromatic core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It features heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Specific substituent patterns and terminal groups define the molecular shape and electronic distribution.
A glucoside of tyrosol found in Rhodiola species.

A rod-like bio-polysaccharide consisting of linear chains of D-glucose units linked by beta-1,4-glycosidic bonds, possessing a twisted needle-like morphology that self-assembles into helical structures.

Nt3 comprises an aromatic organic scaffold with a rigid core, linkers, and flexible side chains. It features heteroatom functional groups and extended conjugation, where substituent patterns define the molecular shape. Ring composition and terminal groups vary to modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

phase_transition_behavior: Cr → Colh → I (Colh→I on heating at 198.7 °C; I→Colh on cooling at 197.6 °C)
description: The molecule is based on a fused dibenzo[a,c]phenazine polycyclic aromatic core featuring two nitrogen atoms within the ring system. Attached to this aromatic framework at the 2, 3, 6, and 7 positions are four hexyloxy chains connected via aryl–O–alkyl ether linkages. At the 11 position, the core is substituted with a carboxylate group that forms an ester linkage with a 3-hydroxypropyl moiety, resulting in a –C(=O)O–CH2–CH2–CH2–OH side chain.
A photochromic spiropyran monomer (referred to as SPEA) used to prepare functionalized stimuli-responsive latex particles.

A biobased polyester synthesized via the two-step melt polycondensation of dimethyl-2,5-thiophenedicarboxylate and 1,4-butanediol. The polymer backbone features a five-membered heteroaromatic thiophene ring linked to a linear four-carbon aliphatic spacer through ester functionalities.

The molecule consists of a central 1,4-phenylene ring connected to two distinct imine (Schiff base) linkages at the para positions. One imine nitrogen is double-bonded to a carbon atom that is part of a 3-phenylallylidene group (a cinnamyl moiety), featuring a conjugated alkene chain terminating in a phenyl ring. The other imine nitrogen is double-bonded to a carbon atom attached to a 4-bromophenyl group, characterized by a benzene ring substituted with a bromine atom at the para position relative to the imine bond.

A chiral organic diester synthesized from hydroxybenzoic acid derivatives and (S)-2-octanol. The structure comprises two phenyl rings connected by an ester linkage, with a hexyloxy chain at one end and a chiral branched alkyl group at the other.

phase_transition_behavior: Cr 97.5 °C (ΔH 68.0 J/g) → Colh 202.9 °C (ΔH 7.7 J/g) → I; on cooling I 202.0 °C (ΔH 7.7 J/g) → Colh
description: Pentyl 2,3,6,7-tetrakis(hexyloxy)dibenzo[a,c]phenazine-11-carboxylate is based on a fused polycyclic dibenzo[a,c]phenazine framework that incorporates two nitrogen atoms within the central phenazine ring system. The aromatic core is substituted at the 2, 3, 6, and 7 positions with hexyloxy groups, where each oxygen atom links the core to a linear six-carbon alkyl chain via an ether bond. At the 11-position, the framework features a carboxylate group esterified with a linear pentyl chain through an O–C(=O) linkage.
Butyl 2,3,6,7-tetrakis(hexyloxy)dibenzo[a,c]phenazine-11-carboxylate is a butyl ester derivative of 2,3,6,7-tetrakis(hexyloxy)dibenzo[a,c]phenazine-11-carboxylic acid.

A symmetrical organic molecule featuring a 3,3'-dimethylbiphenyl core connected via azomethine linkages to two outer aromatic rings. Each of these outer rings is substituted with a methoxy group and an aliphatic hexyloxy chain terminated by a hydroxyl group.

phase_transition_behavior: Crystal → nematic → isotropic on heating; isotropic → crystal on cooling (reported as monotropic).
description: YHD796 is a symmetric croconaine-type conjugated molecule centered on a five-membered croconate ring. This core features two exocyclic carbon-carbon double bonds at the 2- and 5-positions, linking it to two thiophene rings. Each thiophene unit is substituted with a piperidine ring attached via the nitrogen atom (an N-linked piperidin-4-yl moiety). At the 4-position of each piperidine ring, there is a carboxylate group esterified with a linear decyl chain (–O–(CH2)9–CH3), resulting in two identical decyl ester side chains extending from the molecule's periphery.

An anthraquinone derivative naturally occurring in Aloe barbadensis and Rheum palmatum. The chemical structure comprises a tricyclic 9,10-anthracenedione core substituted with hydroxyl groups at the 1 and 8 positions and a hydroxymethyl group at the 3 position. It is a lipophilic compound with poor aqueous solubility, often used as a model drug in the study of lipid-based nanoparticle formulations.

Poly(octadecyl methacrylate) is a polymethacrylate in which the repeating units are connected through a carbon–carbon backbone formed from methacrylate vinyl groups. Each repeat unit bears a pendant ester substituent: a carbonyl group attached to an oxygen atom that links to a linear octadecyl (C18) alkyl chain. The polymer is synthesized from the corresponding octadecyl methacrylate monomer by atom transfer radical polymerisation (ATRP), using an alkyl halide initiator and a transition-metal/ligand catalyst system to grow the chain via reversible halogen-atom transfer.

An amide derivative of L-lysine in which the alpha-amino nitrogen is acylated by a twelve-carbon lauroyl (dodecanoyl) chain. The molecule consists of a linear dodecyl alkyl chain linked to the L-lysine amide moiety.

A pi-conjugated oligomer comprising a terthiophene core flanked by two 3-fluoro-4-alkoxyphenyl groups. The alkoxy substituents are chiral dilactate moieties terminated with butyl esters. The molecule features a rigid aromatic backbone and flexible chiral polar side chains.
A star-shaped heteroaromatic molecule featuring a tristriazolotriazine core substituted with three 3,4-bis(3,3-dimethyloctyloxy)phenyl arms.

A fluorinated tolane derivative featuring a 2,3,5,6-tetrafluorobenzonitrile core coupled to a phenyl ring with a 7,7,8,8,9,9,10,10,10-nonafluorodecyloxy tail. Synthesized via the reaction of pentafluorobenzonitrile with a lithium acetylide intermediate.

A functionalized benzodifuran monomer characterized by a T-shaped donor-acceptor-donor scaffold. The structure includes two amino groups, two butyl ester chains, and a twisted 4-nitrophenyl ring attached to the heterocyclic core. It serves as a building block for the synthesis of Schiff base polymers and complexes, crystallizing with an intermolecular hydrogen-bonded network involving the amino and nitro groups.
An organic ester formed from methoxycinnamic acid and 2-ethylhexanol. The molecule possesses a conjugated system capable of absorbing UVB radiation.

A trifunctional surfactant molecule comprising a hydrophobic heptadecyl alkyl tail, a hydrophilic oligo(ethylene glycol) core block with approximately eight repeat units, and a polar potassium sulfonate end group. The structure combines nonionic and anionic functionalities, designed for surface activity and complexation with hydroxyl-bearing surfaces via the ether oxygens.

Methyl 3-iodobicyclo[1.1.1]pentane-1-carboxylate is an aromatic scaffold featuring a rigid core, linkers, and flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A C3-symmetric heterocyclic compound featuring a tristriazolotriazine core decorated with three 4-decyloxyphenyl groups. The molecule is synthesized by the trimerization reaction involving 5-(4-decyloxyphenyl)tetrazole and cyanuric chloride.

This chemical compound appears as a white solid powder. It features a fluorine atom within its molecular structure. The substance is employed as a building block for synthesizing light-responsive chiral dopants.

4'-Cyano-3',5'-difluoro-2-nitro-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-yl 4-(1,3-dioxan-2-yl)-2,6-difluorobenzoate is a benzoate ester. The molecule consists of a 4-(1,3-dioxan-2-yl)-2,6-difluorobenzoyl moiety attached to a biphenyl core. This core bears 4'-cyano, 3',5'-difluoro, and 2-nitro substituents.

Pentaerythritol is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A water-soluble polyether synthesized from ethylene oxide, comprising flexible ethylene glycol repeating units. It is widely used as a viscosity modifier and binding agent to facilitate polymer chain entanglement.
A methylated furan derivative used as a liquid fuel component. It is synthesized from specific hydroxymethylfurfural isomers.

This chemical entity is a supramolecular complex derived from a tetradecyl-substituted L-DOPA hybrid. It contains a crown ether moiety that coordinates with sodium iodide. The structure is characterized by the interaction between the macrocycle and the alkali metal salt.

A bis-acrylate monomer synthesized via the esterification of 2-phenylhydroquinone with 4-(3-acryloyloxypropyloxy)benzoic acid. The molecule features a rigid terphenyl-like core with a lateral phenyl substituent and two short propyl spacers linking the core to polymerizable acrylate end-groups. Due to the steric hindrance of the lateral group and restricted flexibility of the short spacers, the material crystallizes without forming an intermediate anisotropic fluid phase.
A flexible aliphatic dithiol compound featuring an oligo(ethylene glycol) backbone. It functions as a chain extender in the synthesis of oligomers via thiol-Michael addition chemistry.
A heteroaromatic disk-shaped molecule featuring a central tris([1,2,4]triazolo)[1,5-a:1',5'-c:1'',5''-e][1,3,5]triazine core substituted with three 3,4-dioctadecyloxyphenyl groups.
A fluorescent dye comprising a coumarin heterocyclic core substituted with a benzothiazole ring and a diethylamino electron-donating group.
A fluoropolymer material consisting of repeating vinyl fluoride units.

A nonionic surfactant molecule prepared by coupling acetylated D-xylose with diethylene glycol monoheptyl ether. The structure features a heptyl tail attached to a xylose moiety through a flexible dioxyethylene linker.
A biguanide derivative synthesized from dimethylamine and 2-cyanoguanidine, characterized by two guanidine functions linked together.

The molecule is an imine derivative formed from the condensation of 3-methoxy-4-dodecyloxybenzaldehyde with an amine-functionalized thiadiazole intermediate. Structurally, it consists of a central Schiff base linkage connecting a 3-methoxy-4-dodecyloxyphenyl group to a phenyl ring substituted with a 5-(4-butoxyphenyl)-1,3,4-thiadiazole moiety. The structure is characterized by a lateral methoxy group and a terminal dodecyl chain on one end, with a butoxy chain on the opposing aromatic terminus.

A triblock terpolypeptoid synthesized via sequential ring-opening polymerization of N-substituted N-carboxyanhydrides using a benzyl amine initiator. It consists of a poly(N-allyl glycine) block, a poly(N-methyl glycine) midblock, and a poly(N-decyl glycine) hydrophobic block. In aqueous solution, this polymer self-assembles into spherical micelles with an amorphous core.
A rod-like aromatic hydrocarbon consisting of a p-terphenyl core symmetrically substituted with pentyl chains at the terminal positions.

c-DOPA(16) • KI is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A Schiff base ester derivative comprising a rigid three-ring core with a hexyloxy tail and an unsubstituted phenyl terminus, synthesized by condensing 4-[(4-(hexyloxy)phenylimino)methyl]benzoic acid with phenol.

An amino-functionalized cyclotriphosphazene synthesized by the reduction of its nitro-precursor. The structure consists of a hexasubstituted cyclotriphosphazene core with arms containing Schiff base and amide linkages, each terminated by an amino group.
A tetrahydroxybenzophenone compound. It functions as a UV absorber, protecting formulations from light-induced degradation.

The compound, 2-(4-methylphenyl)-7-tetradecyl[1]benzothieno[3,2-b][1]benzothiophene (pTol-BTBT-C14), consists of a [1]benzothieno[3,2-b][1]benzothiophene core substituted at the 2-position with a 4-methylphenyl group and at the 7-position with a tetradecyl alkyl chain.

phase_transition_behavior: Exhibits smectic phase at 86 °C and nematic phase at 92 °C (trans isomer). Undergoes photo-induced transition to isotropic liquid at these temperatures.
description: Compound 4c is an aromatic organic scaffold with a rigid core, linkers, and flexible side chains. It features heteroatoms and extended conjugation, with substituents defining shape and polarity. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A distyrylbenzene derivative featuring a central benzene ring flanked by two styryl groups. The terminal phenyl rings are substituted with bulky branched 2-octyldodecyl alkoxy chains at the 2 and 4 positions, designed to suppress crystallization and promote a stable fluid state.
A homoleptic aluminum complex coordinated by three 1,3-di-sec-butyltriazenide ligands. Its thermal stability and decomposition pathways are evaluated for ALD suitability.
Layered CdS-OTAB nanocomposite
Layered CdS-CTAB nanocomposite

A trisubstituted ethylene derivative comprising an ethyl ester and a cyano group on one carbon, and a 3-methylphenyl group on the other. This organic molecule is synthesized through the base-catalyzed reaction of 3-methylbenzaldehyde and ethyl cyanoacetate.

A benzoate ester resulting from the formal condensation of 4-iodophenol with 4-[(4-(hexyloxy)phenylimino)methyl]benzoic acid. The molecule features a linear core comprising three phenyl rings: a central benzoate ring linked via an imine (Schiff base) group to a 4-hexyloxyphenyl moiety on one side, and ester-linked to a 4-iodophenyl group on the other. The structure terminates with a hexyloxy chain at one end and an iodine atom at the opposite end.
Symmetric perinone derivative obtained from perylenetetracarboxylic dianhydride and o-phenylenediamine at temperatures > 200 °C. Violet blue substance insoluble in common solvents.

A non-ionic polymer synthesized from the monomer 4-acryloylmorpholine. The structure contains a morpholine ring attached to an acrylamide backbone, providing high thermal stability and compatibility with various polar solvents.
Rigid, rod-shaped nanoparticles composed of highly crystalline cellulose chains, typically featuring surface sulfate ester groups derived from sulfuric acid hydrolysis.

A molecule featuring a decyl alkyl chain attached to a phenyl ring, which is linked via a diazenyl group to a second phenyl ring, forming an azobenzene core. This core is further connected to a tetraethylene glycol chain terminating in a hydroxyl group.

A hexa-substituted cyclotriphosphazene derivative synthesized from hexakis(4-formylphenoxy)cyclotriphosphazene and N-(4-aminophenyl)-4-hydroxybenzamide. The molecule is characterized by six arms containing Schiff base and amide linkages, each terminated by a polar hydroxyl group.

A biodegradable aliphatic polyester derived from renewable resources such as corn starch. It is synthesized via the condensation of 2-hydroxypropionic acid or the ring-opening polymerization of lactide, featuring ester linkages and methyl side groups along the polymer chain.
The molecule consists of a 4-cyano-1,3-phenylene core substituted with two 4-(4-octadecylphenoxycarbonyl)benzoate groups.
A C3-symmetric heteroaromatic compound based on a tristriazolotriazine scaffold substituted with three 4-bromo-3,5-didodecyloxyphenyl groups.

phase_transition_behavior: Table 1 (poly[oxy(hexaethylcyclotetrasiloxane-2,6-diyl)], I-Et) reports Tg = −110 to −112 °C and an isotropization/clearing temperature Ti given as 180–200 °C for one sample; a second entry lists Ti > 275 °C (not reached within the measurement window). Using the explicit phase-transition range, the clearing point is taken as 200 °C (end of the 180–200 °C interval).
description: Poly[oxy(hexaethylcyclotetrasiloxane-2,6-diyl)] is a cyclolinear polysiloxane characterized by a repeating unit containing a four-membered siloxane ring composed of alternating silicon and oxygen atoms. Within this cyclic tetrasiloxane framework, each silicon atom is substituted with ethyl groups. The polymer backbone is formed through oxygen atoms connecting the silicon centers at the 2 and 6 positions of the rings, creating Si–O–Si linkages between adjacent cyclic units.

A phospholipid comprising a glycerol backbone esterified at the sn-1 and sn-2 positions with two oleoyl chains, each containing a cis-double bond. The sn-3 position is linked to a phosphocholine headgroup.

n-Tetradecane is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A π-conjugated molecule featuring a central thiophene ring flanked by two carbazole units, each N-substituted with a 3,4,5-tris(hexadecyloxy)benzyl group. Synthesized via double Suzuki cross-coupling of 2,5-dibromothiophene with a carbazole boronic ester derivative.
Nonyl dioxyethyl alpha-D-xyloside is an amphiphilic molecule consisting of a nonyl alkyl chain linked to an alpha-D-xyloside sugar moiety through a diethylene glycol spacer.

An organic compound consisting of a central cyclohexane-1,3,5-trione ring substituted with three amino(phenyl)methylidene groups. The structure incorporates bulky phenyl substituents that influence the intramolecular hydrogen bonding network and proton mobility via steric and electronic effects. It is a member of the ortho-hydroxyaryl Schiff base family, studied for its stable keto-enamine tautomeric form.
An acetophenone derivative containing a hydroxyl group and a fluorosulfonyloxy group. It is a solid intermediate synthesized for the preparation of acetyl-functionalized polysulfates.

phase_transition_behavior: Not found in provided TABLES or FIGURE CAPTIONS.
description:
This molecule is a cruciform, star-shaped aryl–alkynyl system built on a central benzene core substituted at the 1,2,4,5-positions. Each of the four substitution sites is connected through an ethynyl linker (–C≡C–) to a para-substituted phenyl ring, giving four identical phenylethynyl arms. On each peripheral phenyl ring, the para position carries an octyloxy group (–O–(CH2)7CH3), so the structure contains five benzene rings total (one core plus four peripheral) and four carbon–carbon triple bonds.

A typical synthesis proceeds by first preparing the peripheral arm as a 4-alkoxy-substituted terminal arylacetylene (e.g., via O-alkylation of 4-hydroxy-substituted aryl precursors to install the octyloxy ether, followed by introduction of an ethynyl group). The four arms are then attached to a 1,2,4,5-tetrahalogenated benzene core using a Pd-catalyzed Sonogashira cross-coupling (often with a Cu co-catalyst and base), forming the four aryl–ethynyl C–C bonds that connect the arms to the central ring.

NPG-d6+4+2 is an aromatic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A zinc(II)-coordinated phospholipid derivative featuring a glycerophosphocholine backbone substituted at the sn-1 position with a palmitoyl chain and at the sn-2 position with a metallated pyropheophorbide-a macrocycle.

Rigid, rod-like organic nanoparticles consisting of linear polysaccharide chains of beta(1-4) linked glucose units. These high-aspect-ratio particles organize into helicoidal architectures in aqueous suspension and retain this ordered structure upon drying into solid films.

A crinine-type alkaloid featuring a rigid tetracyclic scaffold with a methylenedioxy moiety, a methoxy group, and a hydroxyl group. This organic molecule is isolated from members of the Amaryllidaceae family and serves as a bioactive agent.

An asymmetric azaacene derivative comprising a pyrazino[2,3-b]quinoxaline core with one dodecyloxy chain and two cyano groups, obtained from the reaction of an alkoxy-substituted phenylenediamine and a dichlorodicyanopyrazine.

A synthetic polypeptide derived from L-glutamic acid, featuring a backbone with side chains containing a benzyl ester para-substituted with a sulfur-protected diphenylphosphine group. This macromolecule adopts an alpha-helical conformation.
A push-pull azo dye comprising a naphthalene core substituted with an amino group and a (4-aminophenyl)diazenyl moiety. It serves as a donor-pi-donor system for two-photon absorption studies.
The amphiphilic hybrid consists of a hydrophilic polymer chain and a hydrophobic dendritic core with two dodecyl tails. It forms spherical aggregates in aqueous solution.
A dithioester compound comprising a benzyl group attached to a dithiobenzoate moiety, commonly used as a chain transfer agent.

This aromatic organic scaffold features a rigid core connected to flexible side chains and heteroatom-containing groups. The structure exhibits extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining shape and polarity. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
An organic ester derived from salicylic acid and 2-ethylhexanol. It appears as a colorless liquid and is widely employed as a UVB filter in topical products.

4'-((4-(4-ethyl-2,6,7-trioxabicyclo[2.2.2]octan-1-yl)-2,6-difluorophenyl)ethynyl)-2',3,5,6'-tetrafluoro-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-carbonitrile is an aromatic organic scaffold. It features a rigid core connected by linkers, substituted with flexible side chains and heteroatom groups.

A fluorinated analog featuring semiperfluorinated lateral chains composed of 4-(perfluorohexyl)butoxy groups attached to a central benzene core. This core is further substituted at the 1 and 4 positions with phenylethynyl arms, which are terminated by expanded oligo(ethylene oxide) glycerol headgroups specifically identified as 2,3-dihydroxypropoxy-triethoxy moieties.

A molecule comprising a central 1,4-phenylene ring connected via two azomethine linkages to distinct terminal groups: one side features a 3-phenylallyl moiety (derived from cinnamaldehyde), while the other terminates in a 4-methoxyphenyl group.

A molecule comprising a central 1,3,4-thiadiazole core flanked by two phenyl rings, one of which is connected via an imine linkage to a third phenyl ring. This outer phenyl ring is substituted with a lateral methoxy group and a terminal butoxy chain, while the phenyl ring on the opposite side of the thiadiazole core also bears a terminal butoxy chain.

phase_transition_behavior: Clearing point (T_NI/T_Iso) not reported in the provided TABLES or FIG CAPTIONS for 5T/dC6/EO3.
description: The molecule is a fully conjugated pentathiophene composed of five thiophene rings connected in series via carbon–carbon single bonds at the 2- and 5-positions. The two terminal thiophene rings are each substituted with an n-hexyl group. Attached to the central thiophene ring via an ether linkage is a tri(ethylene oxide) side chain, which consists of three –CH2–CH2–O– repeating units terminated by a methoxy group.

A nonionic sugar-based surfactant synthesized via the stereoselective coupling of tetra-O-acetyl-D-xylopyranose with diethylene glycol monohexyl ether followed by deacetylation. It consists of a hydrophilic D-xylosyl head group linked to a hexyl chain via a dioxyethylene spacer.

A long-chain saturated fatty alcohol consisting of a fourteen-carbon alkane chain terminated by a hydroxyl group. This organic solid serves as a phase-change material, often employed as a temperature-responsive gatekeeper in mesoporous silica nanocarriers.

C6AzoC4E4 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A partially deuterated triblock terpolypeptoid synthesized via sequential ring-opening polymerization. The structure comprises poly(N-allyl glycine), poly(N-methyl glycine), and poly(N-decyl glycine) segments, where the decyl side chain is fully deuterated. It forms spherical aggregates in water with disordered hydrophobic domains.
A salt formed from a pyrazolium cation and a trifluoromethanesulfonate anion. The presence of the fluorinated group affects the thermal behavior and crystal packing of the material.
A polyester containing a naphthalene ring structure linked by ethylene glycol units.
Monomer with solubilizing chains attached to sulfur atoms.

AETDAB is an aromatic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
The non-proteinogenic D-isomer of the amino acid phenylalanine.

A pi-shaped polyphilic block molecule featuring a p-terphenyl core with two lateral dotriacontyloxy chains at the 2' and 3' positions and polar glycerol units at the 4 and 4'' positions. Synthesized via Suzuki cross-coupling of a 1,2-bis(dotriacontyloxy)-3,6-diiodobenzene intermediate with a boronic acid derivative containing a protected glycerol moiety, followed by acidic deprotection.

A synthetic polypeptide consisting of a poly-gamma-benzyl-D-glutamate backbone where the side chains are modified with a diphenylphosphine sulfide moiety attached via the benzyl ester group. The polymer chain adopts a helical conformation.

phase_transition_behavior: From Table 1, the nematic-to-isotropic transition temperature (TNI) for the MA4 azobenzene unit is reported as 357 K (PMA4, x = 100 mol%), corresponding to a clearing point of 83.9 °C.
description: This molecule is an azobenzene derivative consisting of two benzene rings connected by a central azo linkage (–N=N–). One of the aromatic rings is substituted at the 3-position with a methyl group and at the 4-position with a hexyloxy chain that terminates in a methacrylate ester group (–O–(CH2)6–O–C(=O)–C(CH3)=CH2). The second aromatic ring is substituted at the 4'-position with a linear pentyloxy group (–O–(CH2)5–CH3).
A high-molecular-weight amphiphile featuring a decaglycerol hydrophilic chain attached to a lauric acid moiety.
A myristic acid derivative of decaglycerol consisting of a linear 14-carbon saturated fatty acid chain esterified to a decaglycerol core.

A semi-crystalline polyester obtained from the polycondensation of dimethyl-2,5-thiophenedicarboxylate and 1,6-hexanediol. The chemical structure comprises a thiophene ring alternating with a flexible six-carbon hexamethylene segment along the chain.

A quinacridone derivative methylated at the nitrogen atoms. It features a rigid pentacyclic core containing two ketone and two tertiary amine functionalities. This planar conjugated system facilitates strong intermolecular pi-pi interactions, making it useful as a pigment and organic semiconductor.
A network formed by thiol-Michael addition of a diacrylate monomer featuring a rigid aromatic core to a boronic ester-containing linker and thiol spacers.
A water-soluble organic salt composed of a 3-methylimidazolium cation substituted with an ethyl group, paired with a chloride anion, commonly used as a solvent for biomass processing.

A benzoate ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-[(4-(hexyloxy)phenylimino)methyl]benzoic acid with the hydroxy group of 4-isopropylphenol. It features a central imine linker connecting two benzene rings, with a hexyloxy chain at one end and an isopropyl group at the other.

A fully acetylated glucose derivative featuring a beta-linked azide group at the anomeric position. The molecule contains a linear dipolar functional group attached to a chiral pyranose ring, enabling it to self-assemble into complex solid morphologies.

A long-chain ester derivative comprising a 1-acetyl-4,5-dihydro-1H-pyrazole core substituted with a 4-methoxyphenyl group, connected via a phenyl ring to an azobenzene unit which is ester-linked to a 4-(hexadecyloxy)benzoate moiety.
A functionalized polypeptide derivative of glutamic acid containing a propargyloxybenzyl ester side group, often used as a precursor for click chemistry modifications.

A bis-imine compound synthesized from the condensation of 1,4-phenylenediamine with cinnamaldehyde and 4-dodecyloxybenzaldehyde. Its structure features a central benzene ring connected via imine linkages to a cinnamyl unit on one side and a 4-dodecyloxyphenyl group on the other, the latter terminating in a twelve-carbon alkyl chain.

A tetraphenylethene derivative functionalized with four propyl carbonate groups at the para-positions of the phenyl rings. This molecule serves as a model system to investigate the impact of carbonate ester substituents on the electronic properties and photocyclization kinetics of the central olefinic core, lacking the steric bulk of steroid-based analogues.
A phenolic compound substituted with a vinyl group at the para position.
Layered CdCl2-CTAB precursor complex
A low-corrosive acid solvent used to disperse CNTs for assembly in solution spinning.

phase_transition_behavior: Cryst → SmA → Iso on heating; Iso → SmA → Cryst on cooling (enantiotropic).
description: The molecule is a 3,5-disubstituted 1,2,4-oxadiazole derivative featuring an extended aromatic core. The central 1,2,4-oxadiazole ring is flanked by two para-substituted aromatic systems. At the 3-position, the oxadiazole is bonded to a phenyl ring substituted at the para position with a benzyl ester group (–C(=O)OCH2Ph). At the 5-position, the oxadiazole is attached to a biphenyl unit (two phenyl rings linked by a C–C bond). The terminal phenyl ring of this biphenyl system carries a para-substituent consisting of an ester linkage (–C(=O)O–) connecting to a chiral aliphatic fragment. This fragment is a 3-(decyloxy)-2-methyl-3-oxopropyl group, which contains a stereogenic center and terminates in a decyl ester chain. The overall architecture comprises a linear arrangement of a benzyl ester, a phenyl ring, a 1,2,4-oxadiazole ring, a biphenyl unit, and a chiral alkyl ester tail.

Rotor 13 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
An organic salt comprising a pentamethylguanidinium cation with a long alkoxy chain and a sulfonimide anion with a trifluoromethyl group. Produced by anion exchange of the guanidinium nitrate.
A hydrogen-bonded adduct formed from three molecules of glycine and one molecule of sulfuric acid, crystallizing in a structure known for its pyroelectric sensitivity.

A methyl benzoate derivative substituted with a hydroxyl group and a fluorosulfonyloxy group at the 3 and 5 positions. It is isolated as a solid intermediate during the synthesis of polysulfate monomers.

(S, S)-2 comprises a rigid aromatic core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The framework features heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Its substituent patterns and terminal groups modulate the steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A phospholipid conjugate comprising a glycerol backbone esterified at the sn-1 position with a palmitic acid chain and at the sn-2 position with a pyropheophorbide-a macrocycle, linked to a phosphocholine head group at the sn-3 position. The pyropheophorbide-a moiety features a metal-free tetrapyrrole core.

A homopolymer synthesized from ethyl vinyl ether via cationic polymerization mediated by a dithiocarbamate agent. It exists as an amorphous solid that softens at low temperatures, characteristic of its flexible ether backbone. The material is prepared using a specific photocatalyst to ensure controlled growth.

A symmetric gemini dicationic salt composed of two imidazolium rings connected at the 3-positions by a hexamethylene spacer. Each imidazolium ring is further substituted at the 1-position with a dodecyl chain. The compound incorporates two bromide counterions.

The molecule comprises a fused polycyclic dibenzo[a,c]phenazine core, which integrates two nitrogen atoms within an extended aromatic framework. This central aromatic system is substituted at the 2, 3, 6, and 7 positions with hexyloxy groups, where each substituent features an ether linkage connecting the aryl ring to a linear hexyl chain. At the 11-position, the core is functionalized with a carboxylate group formed as a cyclohexyl ester, consisting of a carbonyl moiety bonded to an oxygen atom that is attached to a cyclohexyl ring.

An organic molecule featuring a central 1,4-phenylene diester core. One terminus is capped with a nitro group attached to a phenoxy ring, while the other terminus consists of a benzoyl group substituted with a lateral butoxy chain at the 2-position and a methoxy group at the 4-position.
An organic compound characterized by a rigid core featuring a lateral methoxy group, which connects a hexyloxyphenyl imine moiety to a 4-chlorobenzoate unit via ester and azomethine linkages.
A disk-shaped molecule featuring a planar tristriazolotriazine central core substituted with three 3,4-didecyloxyphenyl arms.

A quinoxaline derivative comprising a bicyclic heteroaromatic ring system containing two nitrogen atoms. The structure is substituted with two ketone groups at the 2 and 3 positions and two nitro groups at the 6 and 7 positions, functioning as an AMPA receptor antagonist.

An organic-inorganic hybrid molecule featuring a cyclotriphosphazene core substituted with six extended arms. Each arm consists of phenylene rings linked by imine and amide groups, terminated by a dodecyloxy alkyl chain. It is obtained as a yellow powder.
Synthesized via Fisher glycosylation of mannose with a branched C15 alcohol. A surfactant molecule comprising a mannose moiety and a hexahydrofarnesyl tail.
A semi-aromatic nylon produced by the reaction of m-xylenediamine with adipic acid.
Potassium salt of a sulfonimide containing a dodecyloxybenzene moiety and a methylsulfonyl group. Prepared by coupling the sulfonyl chloride with methanesulfonamide.
Beta-substituted bithiophene monomer.
Synthesized from 1,4-butanediol and suberic acid, this aliphatic polymer contains long methylene chains between ester functional groups.

An ethyl ester derivative of a fluorinated tolane, comprising a 2,3,5,6-tetrafluorobenzoate moiety connected via an ethynyl spacer to a phenyl group substituted with a 7,7,8,8,9,9,10,10,10-nonafluorodecyloxy tail.

(S, S)-5 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It contains heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Substituent patterns and terminal groups modulate the steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A trichlorinated derivative of the heptazine core, serving as a reactive starting material for synthesizing polymeric carbon nitrides and other functional materials.
An amphiphilic random copolymer end-capped with a steroidal group, synthesized to form thermo-responsive nanoparticles.

A polycatenar molecule featuring a central 2,2':5',2'':5'',2'''-quaterthiophene core flanked by two 9H-carbazol-3-yl end-groups. Each carbazole unit is N-substituted with a 3,4,5-tris(hexadecyloxy)benzyl moiety, providing six hexadecyloxy chains in total. The structure is synthesized via palladium-catalyzed coupling of a bithiophene boronic ester with a brominated carbazole-thiophene precursor.
A linear conjugated oligomer comprising a core of four thiophene rings linked at the 2,5-positions, symmetrically substituted with hexyl alkyl chains at the terminal alpha-positions.
A molecule consisting of a biphenyl linker connecting two carbazole moieties, often used as a host material in optoelectronic devices.

UUQU-4-N is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Substituent patterns and terminal groups modulate the steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A homoleptic aluminum(III) complex featuring three 1,3-diisopropyltriazenide ligands coordinated to the metal center. It is investigated as a precursor for atomic layer deposition.

Synthesized via the esterification of 4-bromobenzoic acid with methyl 4'-hydroxybiphenyl-4-carboxylate in the presence of dicyclohexylcarbodiimide and dimethylaminopyridine. This organic molecule features a rigid biphenyl core substituted with a methyl carboxylate group at one terminus and a 4-bromobenzoyl moiety attached via an ester linkage at the other. The structure is characterized by an extended pi-conjugated system and intermolecular bromine-oxygen contacts in the solid state.

A chiral polycyclic aromatic compound consisting of six ortho-fused rings, one of which contains a nitrogen atom, resulting in a helical structure. It lacks asymmetric carbon atoms but possesses inherent chirality due to steric repulsion between terminal rings. The molecule is studied for its interaction with biological macromolecules.
A fused tetracyclic thienoacene derivative in which a [1]benzothieno[3,2-b][1]benzothiophene core is substituted with octyl chains at the 2 and 7 positions.

c-DOPA(14) • NaBF4 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A fully protected nucleoside intermediate featuring a cyclic di-tert-butylsilylene protecting group bridging the 3' and 5' hydroxyls.
A branched wax ester synthesized from oleic acid and a C26 iso-branched primary alcohol. It contains a cis-double bond in the acid portion and a terminal isopropyl group in the alcohol portion.

An alpha-cyanoacrylate derivative bearing a para-tolyl moiety attached to the beta-carbon of the propenoate backbone. It is obtained via Knoevenagel condensation and serves as a monomer for radical copolymerization studies.

A fluorinated benzoylthiourea derivative featuring a central thiourea moiety flanked by a benzamide group substituted with two heptyloxy chains at the 3 and 4 positions, and a phenyl ring bearing a perfluorooctyl tail at the 4-position.
A 1:1 supramolecular complex formed through halogen bonding between 4-dodecyloxystilbazole and iodopentafluorobenzene.
A molecular salt synthesized by combining a bicyclic diamine with perrhenic acid, resulting in a structure with high spontaneous polarization.
A biphenyl derivative substituted with a heptyl chain at the 4'-position and a cyano group at the 4-position, featuring an aromatic core of two phenyl rings and an alkyl tail.

A highly symmetric benzene derivative fully substituted with six trimethylsilylethynyl arms, forming a rigid paddle-wheel structure.
An amino acid derivative based on tyrosine, protected by a Boc group on the amine and alkylated with a dodecyl chain on the phenolic oxygen.
A guanosine derivative where the exocyclic amino group is protected as a dimethylformamidine. It is synthesized using N,N-dimethylformamide dimethyl acetal.

The compound is characterized as a brominated derivative of MeCA. It is obtained via a bromination reaction utilizing elemental bromine as the active reagent. This synthetic procedure is carried out in a solution of dichloromethane to afford the target molecule.

A peracetylated mannose derivative with a beta-linked azide group. It differs from the glucose analogue by the axial orientation of the acetyl group at the C2 position, which influences the dimensionality of its self-assembled solid structures.
An amide derivative of glucose specifically modified with an N-acetyl group. It is a monosaccharide chemically related to the structural units of hyaluronic acid and chitin.

The compound is the n=3 dimer, (CN)PNS3SNP(CN), chemically identified as 1,3-bis((6-(4-cyanophenyl)naphthalen-2-yl)thio)propane.

A glycerol monoester comprising a glycerol backbone esterified at one hydroxyl position to a linoleic acid moiety. The molecule features a polar propane-1,2,3-triol headgroup with two free hydroxyl groups and a hydrophobic C18 hydrocarbon tail containing two cis-double bonds at the C9 and C12 positions.

The molecule comprises a central 1,4-disubstituted benzene ring connected via two separate imine (–N=CH–) linkages to distinct terminal groups. One imine nitrogen is attached to a 4-chlorobenzylidene moiety, featuring a benzene ring substituted at the para position with a chlorine atom. The other imine nitrogen is attached to a 3-phenylallylidene group, which consists of a styryl fragment (a benzene ring conjugated with a vinyl group).

A polymer network composed of alternating units derived from 4,4'-biphenol diglycidyl ether and sebacic acid. The backbone features repeating biphenyl moieties connected by aliphatic chains via ester linkages and secondary hydroxyl groups generated from the epoxide ring-opening.
A furan derivative with carboxylic acid groups at the 2 and 4 positions. It is a structural isomer of a common bioplastic monomer and is synthesized from 4-hydroxymethylfurfural.

A distorted rod-like organic molecule synthesized via [3+2] 1,3-dipolar cycloaddition between 4-n-octyloxybenzaldehyde oxime (generated in situ) and 4-tert-butoxystyrene. The structure features a central 4,5-dihydroisoxazole heterocyclic ring substituted at the 3- and 5-positions with phenyl groups. One aromatic ring carries a flexible n-octyloxy chain, while the other bears a bulky tert-butoxy group. The core isoxazoline ring adopts a twist conformation, connecting the two aryl systems in a non-coplanar arrangement.
A molecule consisting of a hydrophobic hexyl chain and a hydrophilic tetraethylene glycol tail, connected by an azobenzene core and a butyl spacer.
Part of a synthesized homologous series of 4,4′-dialkyloxy-3-methylazobenzene derivatives (n=3).
A quaternary ammonium salt consisting of a hexadecyl chain and three methyl groups attached to a central nitrogen atom, balanced by a bromide counterion.
A branched-chain lipid comprising a phytanyl tail attached to a triol headgroup. The molecule features a 3,7,11,15-tetramethylhexadecyl backbone and three hydroxyl groups.
An aminobenzoic acid derivative with the amino group located para to the carboxyl group.

c-DOPA(14) • KSCN is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A bisphenol A-based cyanate ester monomer featuring two cyanate functional groups attached to the aromatic rings. It acts as a thermosetting resin precursor, forming a thermally stable triazine network via cyclotrimerization.

A chlorinated cyclotriphosphazene derivative synthesized by the condensation of hexakis(4-formylphenoxy)cyclotriphosphazene with N-(4-aminophenyl)-4-chlorobenzamide. It possesses a rigid core and six arms containing imine and amide linkages, terminated by chlorine atoms.

An ester-linked molecule containing a 1-acetyl-4,5-dihydro-1H-pyrazole heterocyclic core, a 4-methoxyphenyl substituent, and an azobenzene unit attached to a 4-(octyloxy)benzoate group. Synthesized by esterification of a phenolic azo-pyrazole intermediate with 4-(octyloxy)benzoyl chloride.

Bn10 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
An aromatic hydrocarbon consisting of a benzene ring with a vinyl substituent.
A phosphoramidite monomer derived from 8-trifluoromethylguanosine, equipped with standard protecting groups for use in solid-phase RNA synthesis.

A diester molecule comprising a central 4-oxybenzoate unit linked to a 4-nitrophenyl group and a 2,4,6-trimethoxybenzoate moiety. The structure features a highly substituted terminal aryl ring with three methoxy groups.
A synthetic polypeptide with an alpha-helical backbone, featuring gamma-chloropropyl ester side chains attached to the glutamic acid repeating units.
A fluorene-based aromatic molecule functionalized with a single cyano group, serving as a model system for electron delocalization studies.
A co-crystal formed by the interaction between pyrazole and a hydroxybenzoic acid derivative. The structure relies on hydrogen bonding between the heterocyclic base and the carboxylic acid component.

The molecule comprises a central benzene ring substituted at the 2-position with an acetyl group. This central ring is linked at the 1- and 4-positions via ester bonds to two identical 4-(4-pentenyloxy)benzoate groups, each featuring a terminal alkene functionality on the pentenyloxy chain.
A spherical carbon allotrope composed of sixty carbon atoms. It exhibits strong antioxidant properties and is capable of scavenging reactive oxygen species.
A prototypical donor-acceptor aromatic molecule consisting of an amino group and a nitro group attached to opposite sides of a benzene ring.

A co-crystalline material composed of two equivalents of 4-n-hexyloxybenzoic acid and one equivalent of trans-1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethylene. The components form a linear triad assembly through hydrogen bonding between the carboxylic acid groups and the pyridyl nitrogen atoms, resulting in an elongated rigid core structure flanked by flexible hexyl chains.

A dicationic organic salt featuring two imidazolium rings connected by an ethylene spacer, with each ring bearing a butyl chain. The counterions are tetrafluoroborate. Prepared by reacting 1-butylimidazole with 1,2-dibromoethane and subsequent ion exchange.
A diketopyrrolopyrrole dye flanked by thiophene units and N-substituted with dodecyl alkyl chains.
A triphenylene derivative carrying four pentyloxy substituents at the 2, 7, 10, and 11 positions, along with two ethoxycarbonyl groups located at the 3 and 6 positions.

A cyclotriphosphazene derivative featuring an inorganic heterocyclic P3N3 core substituted with six identical organic side arms. Each arm consists of a phenoxy group linked via an imine (Schiff base) bond to a phenyl ring, which is further connected through an amide linkage to a 4-(nonyloxy)phenyl group. The structure terminates in nonyloxy alkyl chains.
A furan ring substituted with two methyl groups. It is produced via hydrogenolysis of biomass-derived precursors and is utilized as a high-energy density liquid fuel.

A gold(III) complex coordinated by a tridentate C^N^C ligand derived from 2,6-bis(3,4-bis(dodecyloxy)phenyl)pyridine and an ancillary phenylacetylide ligand substituted at the para-position with a 1H,1H,2H,2H-perfluorododecyloxy chain.
A 1:1 intermolecular co-crystal formed between a fully fluorinated benzene ring and an unsubstituted benzene ring, stabilized by quadrupolar interactions.
An anthradithiophene derivative functionalized with triethylsilylethynyl groups to enhance solubility and solid-state packing.

A pi-shaped polyphilic block molecule featuring a p-terphenyl core with two lateral docosyloxy chains at the 2' and 3' positions and polar glycerol units at the 4 and 4'' positions. Synthesized via Suzuki cross-coupling of a 1,2-bis(docosyloxy)-3,6-diiodobenzene intermediate with a boronic acid derivative containing a protected glycerol moiety, followed by acidic deprotection.

A rigid chain polyimide synthesized from pyromellitic dianhydride and 4,4'-diaminoazobenzene. The structure is characterized by a conjugated backbone with flat aromatic imide and azobenzene units, resulting in a semi-crystalline morphology.

A polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon derivative consisting of a rigid triphenylene core substituted with a boronic acid functional group. The molecule is designed to act as an energy donor and can form covalent bonds with hydroxyl-rich polymer matrices.

The molecule is 2,3,8,9,14,15-hexakis(decyloxy)diquinoxalino[2,3-a:2',3'-c]phenazine, which features a diquinoxalino[2,3-a:2',3'-c]phenazine core substituted with six decyloxy chains at the 2, 3, 8, 9, 14, and 15 positions.
A substituted dihydroxybenzene derivative containing a butyl chain attached to the aromatic ring. This organic compound acts as a specific inhibitor of melanin synthesis enzymes.

A semisynthetic tetracycline antibiotic salt featuring a four-ring octahydrotetracene core substituted with dimethylamino and hydroxyl groups. It is utilized for its broad-spectrum antibacterial activity in periodontal treatments.
An organic ester diol featuring a propionate backbone with two hydroxymethyl groups and an ethyl ester moiety, serving as a precursor for cyclic carbonate synthesis.

A nitro-terminated cyclotriphosphazene compound prepared via condensation chemistry. The molecule features six arms attached to a central P3N3 ring, each arm containing Schiff base and amide functionalities ending in a nitro group, known for its electron-withdrawing nature.

A block copolymer synthesized via the ring-opening polymerization of lactide using poly(ethylene glycol) as a macroinitiator and DBU as a catalyst. It features hydrophilic polyether segments covalently linked to hydrophobic polyester chains. The material serves as a biodegradable amphiphilic polymer for hydrophobic coatings and packaging applications.
A mixed-linker zeolitic imidazolate framework containing cadmium, imidazole, and a small amount of benzimidazole. This material is synthesized mechanochemically and can form a glass.

description: Disodium N-dodecylglutamate is an N-substituted glutamate in which the amino nitrogen is bonded to a linear dodecyl (C12) alkyl chain, giving a long hydrocarbon tail attached to the glutamate backbone. Following literature procedures referenced for these amino-acid–based surfactants, the compound is prepared by forming the N–C bond between the glutamate nitrogen and a dodecyl group (N-alkylation to install the C12 chain), then converting the two carboxylic acid functions to their disodium carboxylate form by treatment with sodium base to yield the disodium salt.

A polyfunctional cationic molecule featuring a quaternary ammonium group, a secondary amine, and a hydroxyl moiety. It is obtained by reacting 3-pentadecylphenol with 3-chloropropylamine, followed by the ring opening of N-trimethylammoniumglycidyl chloride.

An organogold(III) complex featuring a [2,6-bis(3,4-bis(dodecyloxy)phenyl)pyridine] pincer ligand coordinated to a gold center, which is further ligated by a 4-(1H,1H,2H,2H-perfluorodecyloxy)phenylacetylide auxiliary ligand containing a semiperfluorinated chain.
A two-dimensional MXene material synthesized via dip-coating, functioning as a transparent conductive electrode and an electrochromic active layer.

A cyclohexane-1,3,5-trione derivative functionalized with three aminomethylidene groups. The molecule features a highly conjugated system with a circular arrangement of hydrogen bonds involving the enamine and keto functionalities. It acts as a fundamental model for examining proton delocalization and structural dynamics in tris-hydroxyaryl enamine derivatives.
Rod-shaped organic nanoparticles featuring a Type-II polysaccharide core with a degree of substitution of 1.64. The surface is extensively modified with acetyl ester functional groups.

A bis-azo dye featuring a naphthalene moiety with an amino donor, linked through a central phenyl group to a terminal phenyl ring. The structure allows for enhanced nonlinear optical response.

An anhydrous supramolecular complex consisting of anionic single-stranded DNA oligonucleotides electrostatically bound to cationic dioctyldimethylammonium bromide surfactants. A Y-shaped push-pull molecule containing a 1-methylimidazole scaffold. It is substituted with 4-(dimethylamino)phenyl groups and linked to a 4-cyanophenyl group via an ethenylene spacer at the 2-position.
A cyclolinear polyorganocarbosiloxane consisting of decamethylcyclohexasiloxane rings linked by ethylene bridges. The structure combines rigid siloxane cycles with flexible hydrocarbon segments.

Monomer used for polymerization.

description: 4,4′-dioctyloxy-3-methylazobenzene is an azobenzene derivative featuring two benzene rings linked by a central azo (–N=N–) bond. Both aromatic rings are substituted at the para (4 and 4′) positions with octyloxy groups, consisting of an oxygen atom attached to a linear eight-carbon alkyl chain. One of the benzene rings is further substituted with a methyl group at the 3-position, located meta to the azo linkage.

description: The molecule consists of a central 1,2,4-oxadiazole ring substituted at the 3- and 5-positions by para-phenylene groups. At the 3-position, the oxadiazole is attached to a phenyl ring which is further substituted at the para-position by a benzyl ester group (–C(=O)OCH2Ph). At the 5-position, the oxadiazole is attached to a biphenyl moiety (two phenyl rings connected by a single bond). The distal ring of this biphenyl system bears a para-substituted ester linkage connecting to a chiral side chain. This side chain comprises a 3-(undecyloxy)-2-methyl-3-oxopropyl group, where the oxygen of the ester linkage is attached to the aromatic ring, and the carbonyl connects to a propionate-derived segment containing a methyl-substituted stereogenic center and a terminal undecyl ester.

An aromatic ester molecule comprising a rigid tri-ring core, specifically a 4-[(3-fluoro-4-nitrophenoxy)carbonyl]phenyl group linked to a 2-octyloxy-4-methoxybenzoate moiety. The structure features a lateral octyloxy chain and a terminal 3-fluoro-4-nitrophenyl group.

A dimeric molecule comprising two rigid aromatic units connected by a flexible tetramethylene spacer. The core structure features ester and imine linkages, and the molecule is terminated at both ends with glycidyl ether groups.
A C3-symmetric aromatic amine consisting of a central benzene ring substituted with three 4-aminophenyl groups, used as a building block for porous frameworks.

A symmetric ketocyanine dye synthesized by condensing croconic acid with a thiophene derivative, featuring a five-membered oxocarbon ring core flanked by thiophene units bearing carboxylic acid-functionalized piperidine rings, designed for strong absorption in the near-infrared region.
An unsaturated decaglycerol ester surfactant containing an oleyl hydrophobic group.
An acrylate monomer containing a linear butyl chain terminated with a hydroxyl group.

A nickel(II) coordination complex comprising a phosphatidylcholine backbone with a palmitoyl chain at the sn-1 position and a pyropheophorbide-a moiety esterified at the sn-2 position, wherein the nickel ion is chelated within the tetrapyrrole macrocycle of the pyropheophorbide-a group.

A carboxyl-functionalized cyclotriphosphazene derivative with a star-shaped topology consisting of a hexafunctional inorganic core bearing six arms. Each arm is composed of a Schiff base linkage connecting a central phenylene unit to the core and a terminal benzoic acid moiety. The molecule features terminal carboxylic acid groups.

A crosslinked polymer network formed from the reaction of a biphenyl diepoxide with a mixture of dithiol spacers and a tetrathiol crosslinker, characterized by beta-hydroxyl thioether linkages connecting the biphenyl cores and thiol-based segments.

A sphingolipid comprising a sphingosine backbone connected via an amide linkage to a hexadecanoyl (palmitic) chain at the C2 position and a phosphocholine moiety attached to the C1 hydroxyl group.

A molecule constructed around a 1-acetyl-4,5-dihydro-1H-pyrazole core substituted at the 3-position with a 4-(octyloxy)phenyl group and at the 5-position with a phenyl ring. This phenyl ring is part of an azobenzene system, linked via a diazenyl group to a second phenyl ring. The para position of this second phenyl ring is esterified with a 4-(tetradecyloxy)benzoate moiety, creating an extended conjugated structure with long alkyl chains at both ends.

An inorganic salt composed of calcium cations and carbonate anions. It is synthesized in this study via a polymer-mediated reaction between calcium chloride and ammonium carbonate, initially forming an amorphous precursor phase that subsequently transforms into a crystalline mineral.
Organic semiconductor used in thin films for nanostructuring case studies on glass and paper substrates. Deposited via PVD (thermal evaporation).
A propargyl ester of 3,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid. This dialkyne-functionalized phenol serves as a starting material for the synthesis of clickable polysulfate monomers.

description: 4,4'-bis(2,3-epoxypropoxy)biphenyl is a molecule constructed around a central biphenyl core, which comprises two benzene rings linked by a single carbon–carbon bond. This aromatic system is substituted at the para positions (4 and 4') with two identical glycidyl ether groups. Each of these substituents features an ether linkage connecting the aromatic ring to a three-carbon chain that terminates in an oxirane (epoxide) ring. Specifically, the structure consists of an –O–CH2–CH–CH2 moiety where the terminal two carbons are bridged by an oxygen atom to form the three-membered epoxide cycle.

A plasmalogen phospholipid consisting of a glycerol backbone substituted with a hexadecenyl vinyl ether at the sn-1 position and a polyunsaturated docosapentaenoyl ester at the sn-2 position, featuring a phosphoethanolamine headgroup.
An aluminum(III) complex featuring three asymmetric 1-isopropyl-3-sec-butyltriazenide ligands. This compound is studied for its thermal properties and potential application in thin film deposition.

This fatty alcohol is characterized by a linear twelve-carbon chain terminating in a primary hydroxyl group. Derived from lauric acid, the structure features a saturated dodecyl backbone. It serves as a precursor for the synthesis of various surfactants.

A fatty acid amide formed by the condensation of the carboxy group of linoleic acid with the amino group of ethanolamine. The molecule features a polar N-(2-hydroxyethyl)amide head group attached to a polyunsaturated C18 hydrocarbon tail containing two cis double bonds at positions 9 and 12.
A long-chain aliphatic polyamide consisting of dodecalactam units, known for low moisture absorption.

A linear polysaccharide consisting of randomly distributed beta-(1-4)-linked D-glucosamine (deacetylated unit) and N-acetyl-D-glucosamine (acetylated unit). The polymer backbone is characterized by primary amine groups located at the C-2 position of the D-glucosamine units.

A hydrogen-bonded adduct comprising a benzoic acid donor and a 3-fluoro-4-nitropyridine acceptor. The presence of the lateral fluorine atom on the pyridine ring modifies the electrostatic properties of the resulting rod-like structure.
An amphiphilic block copolymer consisting of a hydrophilic polyether segment and a hydrophobic biodegradable polyester segment, used to stabilize colloidal dispersions.
A heteroleptic-like aluminum(III) triazenide complex containing isopropyl and tert-butyl groups on the nitrogen ligands. It serves as a volatile precursor for materials science applications.

description:
trans-Perinone (Pigment Orange 43) is a rigid, fully fused polycyclic aromatic system in which two nitrogen-containing annulated ring motifs are incorporated into an extended benzene/naphthalene-like framework. The structure contains multiple ring nitrogens arranged as two fused di-nitrogen heterocycles (benzimidazole/perimidine-type subunits) and several carbonyl groups embedded directly in the fused backbone (lactam/imide-like C=O functionalities), giving a highly conjugated, planar heteroaromatic dione architecture.

It is synthesized by a condensation reaction between a naphthalene tetracarboxylic acid dianhydride (or related mono-/dianhydride precursor) and o-phenylenediamine. The reaction forms the fused N-heterocyclic ring closures onto the aromatic anhydride core to generate a mixture of cis and trans isomers. The trans isomer can then be isolated by exploiting differences in salt formation/solubility via base-induced ring-opening to a potassium salt followed by re-closure/regeneration of the neutral perinone, or by acid-based fractionation of the mixed isomer product.

description:
Disodium N-dodecylaminomalonate is the disodium salt of an aminomalonate derivative in which a straight C12 alkyl chain is bonded to the nitrogen of an aminomalonate unit. Structurally, it contains a linear dodecyl group (–CH3–(CH2)11–) attached via a single C–N bond to an amino-substituted methine carbon that bears two carboxylate groups, giving a malonate-like head group (–CH(COO−)2). The overall anion therefore has one nitrogen atom linking the hydrophobic alkyl chain to the carbon-centered dicarboxylate fragment, and two sodium cations balance the two negative charges of the carboxylates.

The compound is described as being prepared as a disodium salt following previously reported procedures for disodium amino-acid-based surfactants. A typical synthetic connection consistent with this structure is formation of the N–C12 bond by N-alkylation of an aminomalonate/aminomalonic-acid precursor with a dodecyl electrophile (e.g., a dodecyl halide), followed by conversion of the two carboxylic acid/ester groups to the carboxylate form and neutralization with a sodium base to furnish the disodium dicarboxylate.
A simple photochromic molecule consisting of two phenyl rings linked by a diazenyl bridge. It serves as a reference standard for studying photoisomerization dynamics and optical properties.
Elongated nanocrystallites composed of poly(N-acetyl-D-glucosamine) rods with surface charges.

The molecule is built upon a fused polycyclic dibenzo[a,c]phenazine core containing two ring nitrogen atoms. This aromatic framework is substituted at the 2, 3, 6, and 7 positions with hexyloxy groups (–O–(CH2)5CH3), which are attached via aryl–oxygen single bonds. At the 11-position, the core features a carboxyl group modified into an aryl ester, where the carbonyl carbon is bonded to an O–phenyl substituent (–C(=O)O–Ph).
