description:
Molecular structure: The molecule is an acrylate ester (propenoate) in which the acrylate carbonyl is esterified to a linear six-carbon alkyl spacer (hexyl). The terminal carbon of this spacer is connected through an ether oxygen to a para-substituted biphenyl unit. The biphenyl consists of two phenyl rings joined by a single C–C bond, bearing the hexyloxy substituent on one ring and a cyano group (–C≡N) on the para position of the other ring.

Synthesis (connectivity-focused): A common preparation route starts from a para-hydroxy, para-cyano biphenyl intermediate. The phenolic oxygen is alkylated via a Williamson ether synthesis with a six-carbon haloalcohol (or an equivalent protected variant) to install the terminal hydroxyhexyl ether substituent on the biphenyl. The resulting hydroxy-terminated intermediate is then converted to the acrylate by esterification using an activated acrylic acid derivative (e.g., acryloyl chloride) or a coupling-reagent-mediated reaction with acrylic acid, forming the terminal acrylate ester while retaining the biphenyl ether linkage and the nitrile substituent.
Rigid linear polysaccharide nanorods composed of beta-1,4-linked D-glucose units, featuring surface sulfate ester groups.

A sterically crowded hexaphenylbenzene derivative prepared by the cyclotrimerization of a functionalized tolan. The molecule consists of a central benzene ring substituted with six phenyl groups, each bearing a branched alkoxypropyl side chain.
An imidazolium-based ionic compound featuring a butyl substituent and a methyl group on the cationic ring, serving as a medium for chemical synthesis.

A synthetic polyacrylate synthesized via the radical polymerization of isopropyl methacrylate. The polymer structure features a carbon backbone with pendant isopropyl ester groups, typically forming an amorphous solid.

A pyrrolidinium-based ionic salt comprising a five-membered nitrogen heterocyclic cation substituted at the nitrogen atom with one butyl group and one methyl group, paired with a hexafluorophosphate anion.
A fourteen-carbon myristoyl tail is amide-linked to an L-lysine amide moiety, forming a structure with a free amine and a hydrophobic alkyl chain.

BON-LC3-F is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A higher molecular weight telechelic siloxane polymer with a polydimethylsiloxane backbone, end-capped with 4-ethynylbenzamide groups via propyl linkers.
A fluorinated organic compound featuring a tri-s-triazine core bearing three 2,4-difluorophenyl groups, functioning as an electron-transporting material.
An oligomeric organosilicon compound based on 2,2,4,7-tetramethyl-1,3-dioxa-2,4,7-trisilacycloheptane units linked by oxygen. The cyclic unit contains an ethylene bridge within the ring structure.

A thiadiazole-based organic derivative featuring a rigid heteroaromatic core connected via an imine linker to a phenyl ring substituted with a lateral methoxy group and a long octadecyl aliphatic chain. The structure specifically consists of a 1,3,4-thiadiazole unit linked to a 4-butoxyphenyl group on one side and a 4-aminophenyl group on the other, which is condensed with 3-methoxy-4-octadecyloxybenzaldehyde to form the central azomethine bond.
A hydrophobic polymer consisting of a rigid glucose-derived backbone linked by amide bonds, substituted with octyl ether chains, and possessing a theoretical degree of polymerization of 20.

P4VC14P+–Br– is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate the steric bulk and electronic distribution.
An azaacene derivative based on a pyrazino[2,3-b]quinoxaline scaffold, substituted at the 6 and 7 positions with two dodecyloxy chains and at the 2 and 3 positions with two cyano groups.

A fluorinated organic compound comprising a 4-fluorophenyl ester derivative of 4-[(4-(hexyloxy)phenylimino)methyl]benzoic acid, featuring a central imine linkage connecting two phenyl rings and a terminal hexyloxy chain.

A supramolecular polymer complex comprising a poly(1-butyl-4-vinylpyridinium) cationic backbone electrostatically bonded to methyl orange anions. The structure consists of a polyvinylpyridinium main chain with butyl alkyl groups attached to the pyridinium nitrogen atoms, which serve as the cationic sites interacting with the sulfonate groups of the azobenzene-containing methyl orange units.

A symmetrical rod-like organic dye molecule comprising a central biphenyl core linked to two N,N-dibutylaminobenzene moieties via diazenyl bridges. This conjugated bis-azo compound exhibits anisotropic absorption characteristics in the visible spectrum, functioning as a guest material in aligned systems for polarization applications.
A saturated amphiphile consisting of a diglycerol hydrophilic unit linked to an octadecyl chain.

A cellulose derivative in which quaternary trimethyl(2-hydroxypropyl)ammonium groups are attached to the glucose units of the polysaccharide backbone via ether linkages, with chloride serving as the counterion.
Chiral monomer prepared by condensation of (R)-N-(3,5-dinitrobenzoyl)-alpha-phenylglycine with 3-(2-iodoethyl)thiophene.

4'-Cyano-3',5'-difluoro-2-nitro-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-yl 4-(1,3-dioxan-2-yl)benzoate is a benzoate ester containing a substituted biphenyl core. The scaffold incorporates a 1,3-dioxane ring, a nitro group, and difluoro substitution. A terminal cyano group contributes to the extended conjugation.

A synthetic phospholipid based on an sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine scaffold, featuring a saturated hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) chain at the sn-1 position and a 16-fluorohexadecanoyl chain at the sn-2 position.
A trimeric oligofluorene derivative containing three fluorene units and a terminal cyano functional group.

A conductive particulate material synthesized via chemical vapor deposition using volatile polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon byproducts from fuel oil pyrolysis. Its structure comprises aggregated spherical primary particles formed through thermal cracking and deposition processes, widely used as a conductive additive.
Produced via the [2+2+2] cycloaddition of a triphenylene-based alkyne monomer. The molecule features a central benzene core linked to three peripheral triphenylene discs via nonyl ether chains.
Fluorescent dye incorporated into the LCN material to amplify the photo-softening effect.
Synthesized via Fisher glycosylation of xylose with a branched C15 alcohol. A non-ionic surfactant consisting of a xylopyranose head group and a branched alkyl tail.
A lead-free organic-inorganic hybrid material adopting a perovskite architecture, composed of a methylated bicyclic diamine cation, ammonium, and iodine ions.

A Schiff base derivative formed from the reaction of 1,4-phenylenediamine, cinnamaldehyde, and 4-hydroxybenzaldehyde. It contains a central phenylene core with bis-imine linkages, terminating in a phenylpropenyl group and a phenol group.

A triphenylene derivative featuring a core substituted with five pentyloxy chains at the 3, 6, 7, 10, and 11 positions, and a single 4-pentynyloxy group at the 2 position, incorporating a terminal alkyne functional group.

An organic compound comprising a 1-acetyl-4,5-dihydro-1H-pyrazole ring, a 4-methoxyphenyl group, and a 4-((4-(tetradecyloxy)phenyl)diazenyl)phenyl unit. It is synthesized by reacting a chalcone with hydrazine hydrate in the presence of acetic acid.

This simple salt comprises a protonated pyrazole species paired with a chloride counterion. It serves as a baseline material for comparing thermal properties with other pyrazolium salts containing complex anions.
Hydrophobic derivative of vitamin C loaded into monoolein aqueous dispersions as an antioxidant model drug.

A diphenylacetylene derivative symmetrically substituted with ether-linked branched alkyl chains. Synthesized via a palladium-catalyzed cross-coupling reaction between 4,4'-bis(bromophenyl)acetylene and an organoboron intermediate generated from an allyl ether derivative.

description: PAEPKI-C16 is a lipidated hexapeptide consisting of the amino acid sequence Pro–Ala–Glu–Pro–Lys–Ile. The molecule features a free secondary amine at the N-terminal proline. The peptide backbone comprises consecutive amide linkages connecting the α-amino and α-carboxyl groups of the residues. Structurally, the sequence includes two proline residues, each containing a five-membered pyrrolidine ring fused to the backbone via a secondary amide nitrogen. The side chains correspond to alanine (methyl), glutamic acid (a 2-carboxyethyl group), lysine (a 4-aminobutyl group), and isoleucine (a sec-butyl group). At the C-terminus, the carboxyl group of the isoleucine residue is modified into a secondary amide through linkage with a hexadecylamine moiety, resulting in a linear 16-carbon saturated alkyl chain attached via a –C(=O)NH– bond.
An aromatic hydrocarbon polymer made from the styrene monomer.
A disubstituted furan compound with two hydroxymethyl groups. It is derived from 4-hydroxymethylfurfural and serves as a precursor for biologically active compounds.

An unsymmetrical bent-core compound featuring a central 1,3,4-thiadiazole ring linked to a phenyl ring, which is connected via an imine bond to a 3-methoxy-4-(octyloxy)phenyl moiety. The structure is capped with a butyl ether chain on one end and an octyl ether chain on the other.
A terthiophene-based conjugated polymer featuring hexyl side chains, utilized for studying the effect of chain length on film structure.

An organosilicon compound featuring a five-carbon alkyl chain bonded to a trichlorosilyl headgroup. This molecule acts as a precursor for depositing hydrophobic coatings on surfaces rich in hydroxyl groups, forming siloxane networks.
A crystalline gold(III) complex bearing a 3,4,5-tris(semiperfluorooctyloxy)phenylacetylide ligand. The molecule is highly fluorinated on one terminus, creating a distinct amphiphilic structure.
A symmetrical bis-amino substituted azo compound where two aniline rings are connected by a central diazenyl bridge. It represents a donor-pi-donor architecture utilized in nonlinear optics.

A linear polysaccharide macromolecule consisting of beta-1,4-linked D-glucose repeating units with abundant hydroxyl groups. Synthesized by dissolving skimmed cotton in 1-allyl-3-methylimidazolium chloride, followed by wet-spinning into ethanol and supercritical drying, resulting in a regenerated material with the Cellulose II crystal structure and a hierarchical nanofibrous network.

The molecule is based on a fused dibenzo[a,c]phenazine polycyclic aromatic core, which contains a central phenazine unit with two nitrogen atoms. This aromatic scaffold is substituted at the 2, 3, 6, and 7 positions with four hexyloxy groups (–O–(CH2)5CH3). Additionally, the core features a carboxylate group at the 11 position, which is esterified to form an isopropyl ester (–C(=O)OCH(CH3)2).
A tetra-ortho-fluorinated azobenzene core substituted with two reactive acyl chloride groups at the para positions. Prepared from the corresponding dicarboxylic acid using thionyl chloride.

This compound functions as a four-carbon sugar alcohol featuring a backbone substituted with four hydroxyl groups. In addition to its specific chemical architecture, the substance exhibits a high enthalpy of fusion and serves as an ingredient within food products.

A cyclotriphosphazene derivative featuring a star-like structure with six rigid arms. Each arm consists of a 4-nitrophenyl group connected to the central phosphazene ring through a bis(Schiff base) linker system. The molecule is characterized by electron-withdrawing nitro groups at the terminal positions and an inorganic core.

A biphenyl-based compound substituted with an octyloxy group and a cyano functionality at opposite ends of the aromatic core. Its structure consists of a rigid rod-like central unit attached to a flexible alkyl chain, enabling the formation of organized fluid states.
A synthetic polymer produced from hexamethylenediamine and sebacic acid.

A piperidine alkaloid featuring a piperidine ring amide-linked to a piperic acid moiety, which contains a conjugated diene system and a benzodioxole group. It is a major pungent constituent derived from the fruit of black pepper.

A cationic imidazolium derivative featuring a photoactive azobenzene moiety tethered by a pentyl spacer. This amphiphilic molecule is designed to undergo reversible photoisomerization and participate in host-guest interactions with macrocycles like cyclodextrins, enabling the formation of light-responsive supramolecular assemblies.
A lipopeptide consisting of the heptapeptide sequence Trp-Gly-Gly-Arg-Gly-Asp-Ser N-acylated with a myristoyl group.
A naturally occurring pentahydroxyflavone. This polyphenol features a fused bicyclic ketone system substituted with a phenyl group, widely distributed in plant tissues.

The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
An orange fluorescent dye (referred to as HPNIC) used in conjunction with DBTEO in nanoparticles.
A cyclolinear polyorganocarbosiloxane composed of 1,3-dimethyl-1,3-disilacyclobutane rings connected by oxygen bridges. The four-membered rings are highly strained.

A coordination compound featuring a gold(III) center coordinated by a 2,6-bis(4-dodecyloxyphenyl)pyridine pincer ligand and a phenylacetylide ligand substituted at the 3 and 4 positions with 1H,1H,2H,2H-perfluorooctyloxy chains.

A square-planar gold(III) complex comprising a 2,6-bis(4-dodecyloxyphenyl)pyridine pincer ligand coordinated to the metal center, along with a 4-(1H,1H,2H,2H-perfluorododecyloxy)phenylacetylide auxiliary ligand. The structure is characterized by two dodecyloxy hydrocarbon chains attached to the pincer framework and a single semiperfluorinated dodecyloxy chain extending from the acetylide ligand.

A pi-shaped polyphilic block molecule featuring a p-terphenyl core with two lateral triacontyloxy chains at the 2' and 3' positions and polar glycerol units at the 4 and 4'' positions. Synthesized via Suzuki cross-coupling of a 1,2-bis(triacontyloxy)-3,6-diiodobenzene intermediate with a boronic acid derivative containing a protected glycerol moiety, followed by acidic deprotection.
A water-soluble cyclic ester featuring a five-membered lactone ring with an enediol motif and a dihydroxyethyl side chain, widely used as an antioxidant.

description: This molecule is a hexasubstituted benzene derivative featuring a central aromatic ring attached to five aryl–ethynyl arms and one long-chain alkoxy substituent. The five aryl–ethynyl groups are identical, each consisting of a carbon–carbon triple bond linking the central core to a para-substituted phenyl ring, which in turn carries a pentyloxy group connected via an ether linkage. The sixth position on the central benzene ring is substituted with an undecyloxy chain that terminates in a primary hydroxyl group, attached to the core through an ether bond. The overall structure comprises a central benzene core, five peripheral 4-(pentyloxy)phenylethynyl units, and a single 11-hydroxyundecyloxy chain.

Composed of a pyrazolium cation and a benzenesulfonate anion, this material forms a crystalline solid. The compound is characterized by an aromatic sulfonate counterion which influences its thermal properties.
A conjugate molecule comprising an adenine nucleobase linked to a triphenylamine core through a linear butyl spacer, where the triphenylamine unit is substituted with two dodecyloxy chains.

A synthetic amphiphile comprising a cholest-5-en-3-yl steroid core connected to a disaccharide head group via a butyl-acetamide spacer. The carbohydrate unit features a lateral octyl chain attached through a carbamate linkage at the 2-O position.

phase_transition_behavior: Cr 98.9 I (no N–I transition reported in Table 1 for I6c; direct solid-to-isotropic transition inferred from the missing N–I entry).
description:
Molecular structure: The molecule is a Schiff-base/aryl-ester architecture built from three benzene rings. One terminal ring bears a para-hexyloxy substituent (–O–(CH2)5CH3) and is connected through an azomethine linkage (–N=CH–) to a second aromatic ring. This central ring carries a methoxy substituent (–OCH3) and is further substituted by an aryl benzoate group, where the central ring oxygen is esterified to an unsubstituted benzoic acid moiety (–O–C(=O)–Ph).

Synthesis: A typical route proceeds by first forming the aryl benzoate via benzoylation (e.g., converting a phenolic benzaldehyde precursor into the corresponding 4-formyl aryl benzoate using a benzoic-acid derivative such as benzoyl chloride under basic conditions). The resulting aldehyde-containing benzoate is then condensed with a para-hexyloxy-substituted aniline to generate the azomethine (C=N) bond, yielding the final imine-linked aryl benzoate.
An aliphatic polyester produced through the reaction of sebacic acid and 1,4-butanediol, possessing a flexible backbone with significant hydrophobic character.

A metallo-phospholipid conjugate consisting of a central cobalt(II) ion chelated within a pyropheophorbide-a macrocycle, which is esterified to the sn-2 position of a glycerophosphocholine backbone, with a palmitoyl chain attached at the sn-1 position.

A perfluorinated aromatic compound featuring a central 1,4-phenylene ring flanked by two pentafluorophenyl groups. It is synthesized by copper-catalyzed coupling of potassium pentafluorobenzoate and 1,4-diiodobenzene.
Synthesized via Fisher glycosylation of glucose with 3,7,11-trimethyl-dodecan-1-ol. A non-ionic surfactant featuring a glucose polar head and a branched alkyl chain.
An aliphatic polymer synthesized via polycondensation of succinic acid and 1,4-butanediol, containing ester linkages along a flexible backbone.
A pi-extended heteroacene molecule featuring a quinoxalino[2,3-b]quinoxaline core substituted with two dodecyloxy chains at the 9 and 10 positions and a single cyano group at the 2 position.

Br3DiKTa is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

Hexyl 2,3,6,7-tetrakis(hexyloxy)dibenzo[a,c]phenazine-11-carboxylate is a dibenzo[a,c]phenazine derivative substituted at the 2, 3, 6, and 7 positions with hexyloxy groups and at the 11 position with a hexyloxycarbonyl group.
A functional acrylate monomer featuring a primary alcohol and a polymerizable vinyl group, commonly employed in the fabrication of hydrogels and biomedical polymers.
A water-soluble fluorescent cyanine dye featuring two indole rings connected by a polymethine bridge and substituted with sulfonate groups.

A stable organic radical consisting of a central trivalent carbon atom substituted with three 4'-bromo-2,3,5,6-tetrachlorobiphenyl moieties. It appears as a dark green solid and is utilized for on-surface self-assembly studies.
An organic ester specifically designed for UVA protection. Its structure comprises a hexyl benzoate moiety linked to a diethylamino hydroxybenzoyl group.

An ethyl 2-cyano-3-phenyl-2-propenoate derivative carrying a trifluoromethyl substituent at the ortho position of the aromatic ring. It is synthesized via the piperidine-catalyzed reaction of 2-(trifluoromethyl)benzaldehyde with ethyl cyanoacetate.
A diester compound synthesized from 2,4-dimethylbenzoic acid and a 4-nitrophenyl 4-hydroxybenzoate intermediate. It is characterized by two methyl groups on the terminal phenyl ring.

c-DOPA(16) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

phase_transition_behavior: Clearing point (T_NI/T_Iso) for allyl dithiol is not reported in the provided TABLES or FIGURE CAPTIONS.
description: Allyl dithiol (SMILES: C=C(CS)CS) is a small acyclic organosulfur molecule built on a three-carbon framework containing a terminal carbon–carbon double bond. Two thiol functionalities are present as thioether-linked methylene thiols (–CH2–SH): one attached directly to the substituted alkene carbon as a sulfanylmethyl substituent, and one at the adjacent carbon as a terminal –CH2–SH group. In the cited work, allyl dithiol was prepared using a previously documented literature synthesis and its identity was verified by NMR prior to use as a dithiol comonomer in thiol–Michael addition with acrylate-containing reagents.
A long-chain alkylated molecule built on a planar indeno[1,2-b]fluorene framework, where the core is modified with dicyanovinylene units and 3-hexadecylthiophene groups.

An amino-functionalized hexasubstituted cyclotriphosphazene compound. The molecule comprises a central inorganic ring substituted with six side chains, each terminating in a primary amine group linked via a bis(Schiff base) spacer. Synthesized by the reduction of the corresponding nitro-terminated precursor. The electron-donating amino groups influence the molecular packing and electronic properties of the star-shaped assembly.
A symmetrical diester comprising a central 2-methoxy-1,4-phenylene core bonded to two 4-(4-pentenyloxy)benzoate groups.

Pentaglycerine is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

phase_transition_behavior: Clearing point (T_NI/T_Iso) for 4′-Acetoxybiphenyl-4-carboxylic acid was not reported in the provided TABLES or FIGURE CAPTIONS, and no phase-sequence entry for this compound appears there to infer it.
description:
4′-Acetoxybiphenyl-4-carboxylic acid consists of a biphenyl framework (two benzene rings linked by a single C–C bond). One phenyl ring bears a para carboxylic acid substituent (–C(=O)OH). The other phenyl ring carries a para acetoxy substituent (–O–C(=O)CH3), i.e., a phenolic oxygen converted into an acetate ester.

A plausible synthetic route is acetylation of the corresponding hydroxy-biphenyl carboxylic acid precursor: the phenolic –OH group on 4′-hydroxybiphenyl-4-carboxylic acid is converted to the acetate (–O–C(=O)CH3) using an acetylating agent such as acetic anhydride, followed by standard isolation and purification to give the mono-acetylated product while retaining the free carboxylic acid.
A trichotomous amphiphile consisting of a rigid steroidal unit, a polar disaccharide, and a lateral dodecyl chain connected via a carbamate group.
A silylated diaryl sulfone monomer containing a tert-butyldimethylsilyloxy group and a fluorosulfonyloxy group. This compound is used as an AB-type monomer in SuFEx polycondensation.

phase_transition_behavior: Crystal → isotropic liquid (direct clearing, no intermediate mesophase indicated for the n = 6 derivative).
description: This compound is an azobenzene consisting of two benzene rings linked by an azo double bond (–N=N–). Each aromatic ring bears a para-position hexyloxy substituent (–O–(CH2)5–CH3), and one ring additionally carries a methyl group at the meta position relative to the azo linkage, giving an unsymmetrical substitution pattern. A common synthetic approach is to construct the central azo linkage by converting a substituted aniline into the corresponding aryl diazonium intermediate and coupling it to an electron-rich, substituted aromatic partner to form the Ar–N=N–Ar framework; the para hexyloxy substituents can be installed by O-alkylation (Williamson ether formation) of the corresponding phenolic precursors with a hexyl halide, with the methyl substituent originating from the appropriately substituted aromatic starting material.

A porous coordination polymer comprising zinc centers bridged by a combination of imidazolate and 2-methylbenzimidazolate linkers. This framework demonstrates glass-forming ability and retains porosity in the amorphous state.

A central benzene ring substituted at the 1, 2, and 4 positions with methylene ether bridges, each connecting to a triphenylene unit. Each of the three triphenylene moieties is further substituted with five pentyloxy chains at the 3, 6, 7, 10, and 11 positions.

An organic semiconductor consisting of repeating phenylene and amine units. It can exist in various oxidation states such as leucoemeraldine, emeraldine, and pernigraniline, and is synthesized by the oxidative coupling of amino-substituted benzene monomers.

A synthetic organic solid characterized by a resorcinol core substituted with a 1-phenylethyl moiety. It functions as a potent tyrosinase inhibitor and is widely used in formulations for skin brightening.

A two-dimensional hybrid organic-inorganic perovskite synthesized from pentylammonium iodide and lead(II) iodide. It consists of inorganic lead iodide layers separated by organic pentylammonium spacers.

4-octyl-4′-cyanobiphenyl consists of a biphenyl scaffold, comprising two benzene rings linked by a single C–C bond. One of the aromatic rings is substituted at the para position relative to the biaryl linkage with a linear n-octyl group (an eight-carbon saturated alkyl chain), while the other ring is substituted at the para position with a cyano group (a carbon–nitrogen triple bond).

A supramolecular assembly formed by hydrogen bonding between a dimethoxy-substituted benzoic acid derivative and 4-nitropyridine. The complex features a linear, rod-like geometry stabilized by the interaction between the carboxylic acid and pyridine nitrogen.
A six-membered cyclic acetal containing two oxygen atoms at the 1 and 3 positions. It is a colorless liquid produced from the depolymerization of polyoxymethylene.

A conjugated ester derivative containing a 3-(2,4-dimethoxyphenyl)acryloyl group attached to a 4-nitrophenyl 4-oxybenzoate core. The structure includes a vinyl linker and two methoxy groups on the terminal aromatic ring.

This compound is a linear, two-coordinate gold(I) complex in which a single Au(I) center is bonded to two carbon-based ligands. One ligand is an isocyanide, with the gold bound to the isocyanide carbon of a pentyl isocyanide fragment (pentyl–N≡C–). The other ligand is an alkynyl derived from a biphenyl-ethynyl unit, where Au is σ-bonded to the terminal carbon of a C≡C group that is conjugated into a 4,4′-disubstituted biphenyl system; one phenyl ring bears an ethoxy substituent (–O–CH2–CH3) at the para position relative to the biaryl bond, and the opposite ring is connected at its para position to the ethynyl linkage (–C≡C–Au).

Synthesis proceeds by first generating the gold–alkynyl fragment from a 4-alkoxybiphenylacetylene precursor (here, the ethoxy-substituted biphenyl acetylene) and a chlorogold(I) tetrahydrothiophene complex, using acetate base to form the Au–C≡C bond. The resulting alkynylgold(I) intermediate is then treated with 1-pentyl isocyanide, which coordinates to gold through the isocyanide carbon to furnish the (alkynyl)(isocyanide)gold(I) complex.

A distyrylbenzene-based fluorophore with branched 2-octyldodecyl alkoxy chains attached to the 3 and 5 positions of the terminal phenyl rings, showing a solid-to-fluid change slightly above room temperature.

A gold(III) complex coordinated by a pincer ligand based on a 2,6-bis(3,4-bis(dodecyloxy)phenyl)pyridine core, which features four dodecyloxy chains attached to the phenyl rings. The coordination sphere is completed by a mono-substituted phenylacetylide ligand bearing a 4-(1H,1H,2H,2H-perfluorooctyloxy) tail.

A commercial bifunctional epoxy resin monomer derived from bisphenol A. It consists of two benzene rings connected by a flexible isopropylidene bridge and capped with glycidyl ether groups, widely used in coatings and adhesives.
A disk-like heteroaromatic molecule comprising a tristriazolotriazine core bearing three 3,4,5-tridodecyloxyphenyl groups.

An organic compound comprising two 4'-cyanobiphenyl units linked by a hexyl spacer, where one unit is attached via an ether bond at the 4-position and the other is attached via a direct carbon-carbon bond at the 4-position.
A nitrogen-containing pentacene analogue (azaacene) with triisopropylsilylethynyl solubilizing groups.

A zwitterionic glycerophospholipid consisting of a glycerol backbone linked to a phosphocholine head group at the sn-3 position, a hexadecenyl vinyl ether chain at the sn-1 position, and a docosapentaenoyl ester chain at the sn-2 position.

A hydroquinone derivative featuring a hydroxyl group and a long alkyl chain terminating in a polymerizable acrylate ester. Synthesized via etherification of hydroquinone with a functionalized nonyl bromide.

A gold(III) coordination compound consisting of a [2,6-bis(3,4-bis(dodecyloxy)phenyl)pyridine]gold(III) cation coordinated to a 3,4,5-tris(1H,1H,2H,2H-perfluorodecyloxy)phenylacetylide anion, featuring four dodecyloxy chains and three semiperfluorinated decyloxy chains attached to the aromatic core.
A bridged organosilica precursor containing an ethylene moiety between two reactive triethoxysilyl groups, used to synthesize robust hybrid materials.
An amphiphilic tricarbocyanine molecule featuring two polycyclic benzoindole ring systems linked by a heptamethine polymethine chain, substituted with sulfobutyl groups to enhance water solubility.
A donor-acceptor-donor organic molecule featuring a central electron-deficient benzothiadiazole unit flanked by two electron-rich thiophene rings. It serves as a yellow-emitting fluorescent dye.
Part of a synthesized homologous series of 4,4′-dialkyloxy-3-methylazobenzene derivatives (n=5).

An organic compound featuring a 1-acetyl-4,5-dihydro-1H-pyrazole ring, a 4-butoxyphenyl group, and an azobenzene moiety esterified with a 4-(decyloxy)benzoate chain. Prepared by esterification of the corresponding phenolic intermediate.

A functionalized conducting polymer derived from a five-membered nitrogen heterocycle bearing a carboxylic acid moiety at the 3-position. The presence of the carboxyl group allows for further covalent modification and bioconjugation.

A salt featuring a protonated tetramethylguanidinium cation linked to a dodecyloxyphenyl moiety and a trifluoromethyl-sulfonimide anion. Synthesized by refluxing the chloride salt with the potassium sulfonimide.

Trihexyl(tetradecyl)phosphonium bis(4-ethylcatecholato)borate is an aromatic scaffold with a rigid core connected by linkers and flexible side chains. It features heteroatom-containing groups and extended conjugation. Substituent patterns define the shape, while ring composition modulates steric bulk.

3',4',5'-trifluoro-2-nitro-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-yl 4-(1,3-dioxan-2-yl)-2,6-difluorobenzoate is a benzoate ester. It features a 2,6-difluorophenyl ring substituted with a 1,3-dioxan-2-yl group, ester-linked to a 3',4',5'-trifluoro-2-nitro-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-yl moiety.

A pi-shaped polyphilic block molecule featuring a p-terphenyl core substituted with two lateral octadecyloxy chains at the 2' and 3' positions and glycerol units at the 4 and 4'' positions. The compound is synthesized via Suzuki cross-coupling of a 1,2-bis(octadecyloxy)-3,6-diiodobenzene intermediate with a boronic acid derivative containing a protected glycerol moiety, followed by acidic deprotection.

A manganese(II) phospholipid complex in which a manganese(II) ion is coordinated by a pyropheophorbide-a moiety located at the sn-2 position of a glycerophosphocholine backbone, with a palmitoyl chain at the sn-1 position.
A halogenated organic ester featuring a 4-iodo-2-methoxyphenyl group attached to a central 4-oxybenzoate core. The molecule terminates with a 4-nitrophenyl moiety.
An imidazolium-based ionic liquid surfactant featuring a long octadecyl chain.

An imidazolium-based dicationic compound with two hexyl chains attached to the nitrogen atoms of the heterocycles, linked via an ethylene unit. It contains tetrafluoroborate anions and is synthesized through alkylation followed by metathesis.
An azo dye featuring a phenyl group connected to a 4-aminophenyl moiety via a diazenyl linkage. This structure creates a donor-pi system commonly used in optical studies.
A microbial copolymer composed of 3-hydroxybutyrate and 3-hydroxyhexanoate units.
An N-carboxyanhydride monomer synthesized from cysteine, featuring a sulfur atom protected by a photo-labile o-nitrobenzyl moiety.
An amorphous polymer containing carbonate groups, typically derived from bisphenol A and phosgene.

A pi-conjugated oligomer consisting of a central benzene ring substituted with two bulky 3,4,5-tris(dodecyloxy)benzyl groups and two 4-carboxyphenylethynyl arms. The molecule features terminal carboxylic acid groups capable of hydrogen bonding, alongside an extended aromatic core and long alkyl chains.
A symmetric dimer consisting of two biphenyl cores with terminal nitrile groups, linked by a pentamethylene spacer.
Rigid nanorods composed of bundled polysaccharide chains with sulfate half-ester groups grafted onto the surface.

A gold(III) pincer complex coordinated by a 2,6-bis(4-dodecyloxyphenyl)pyridine ligand and a 3,4-bis(1H,1H,2H,2H-perfluorododecyloxy)phenylacetylide ligand. The structure consists of a central Au(III) ion bound to the tridentate C^N^C pincer framework, which is substituted with two dodecyloxy chains, and an ancillary phenylacetylide group bearing two semiperfluorinated dodecyloxy chains at the 3 and 4 positions.

c-DOPA(14) • KI is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
An organic precursor synthesized from 3-chloro-2-(chloromethyl)-1-propene and potassium ethyl xanthogenate. The molecule features a 2-methylenepropane core substituted with two ethyl xanthate groups.

A cationic polymerizable surfactant consisting of a methacrylate ester group connected via an ethyl spacer to a quaternary ammonium headgroup, which bears two methyl groups and a tetradecyl chain, with bromide as the counterion.
A water-soluble surfactant derived from decaglycerol and octanoic acid, which self-assembles into nanostructures in aqueous solution.

This aromatic organic scaffold features a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It exhibits extended conjugation and heteroatom-containing functional groups. Substituent patterns, ring composition, and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A six-membered fluorinated heterocycle featuring a 1,2-oxazine core with an internal oxygen-nitrogen bond. Synthesized via ring-closing metathesis (RCM) of a trisubstituted olefin precursor, this molecule contains a fluorine atom substituted on the carbon-carbon double bond within the ring.
An organic molecule comprising three benzene rings connected by ester linkages, featuring a long lateral nonyloxy chain and a fluorinated nitrophenyl terminus.

A carboxylic acid-functionalized cyclotriphosphazene obtained as an orange powder. Its structure comprises a phosphazene core and six arms featuring Schiff base and amide groups, terminating in carboxylic acid moieties.
A rigid, rod-like polysaccharide nanoparticle featuring a highly ordered crystalline structure composed of beta-1,4-linked glucose units.
A fluoropolymer consisting entirely of carbon and fluorine, known for chemical inertness.
Monomer isolated in 83% yield.

A linear aromatic ester molecule comprising three benzene rings connected by carboxylate linkages. The structure features a rigid core terminated by a nitro group at one end and a 2,4-dimethoxybenzoyl group at the other.

A heavily fluorinated organogold derivative synthesized by coupling a 2-chain pincer complex with a tris(semiperfluorodecyloxy)phenylacetylene. It forms a crystalline solid with multiple solid-state forms.

A cholesterol ester resulting from the formal condensation of the 3-hydroxy group of cholesterol with the carboxy group of 22-methyltetracosanoic acid. The fatty acid component is a C25 anteiso-branched chain, characterized by a methyl substituent at position 22.
A pharmaceutical salt comprising a benzhydryl derivative with a phenol moiety and a diisopropylamino group, paired with a dihydroxysuccinic acid counterion.
A tri-aryl ester featuring a lateral hexyloxy chain and a fluorine atom located on the nitro-substituted terminal ring.

A tris-substituted cyclohexane-1,3,5-trione derivative featuring three 1-aminoethylidene groups symmetrically attached to the ring carbons. The molecule possesses a conjugated system stabilized by intramolecular hydrogen bonds between the amino hydrogens and the carbonyl oxygens. It serves as a model for investigating tautomeric equilibria and proton transfer dynamics in cyclic organic systems.

A cyano-substituted distyrylbenzene derivative where the vinylene linkages bear cyano groups. The terminal aromatic rings are functionalized with long branched 2-decyltetradecyl alkoxy chains at the 2 and 5 positions.

A crosslinked polymer network comprising alternating units of 4,4'-diglycidyloxyazobenzene and dodecanedioic acid linked via ester bonds, with secondary hydroxyl groups present on the glycidyl segments resulting from epoxide ring opening.
Intermediate 8. White solid.
A ceramide consisting of a sphingosine backbone connected via an amide linkage to a hexadecanoyl (palmitic acid) chain, characterized by the absence of a phosphate group.
A pyridine derivative containing a Schiff base and ester linkage, consisting of a 4-{[(pyridin-4-yl)methylidene]amino}phenyl core substituted with a 4-tetradecyloxybenzoate group.

A star-shaped trimer consisting of a central benzene ring substituted at the 1, 2, and 4 positions with octyl spacers, which link to three triphenylene units via ester groups. Each triphenylene unit is further substituted with five pentyloxy chains at the 3, 6, 7, 10, and 11 positions.
A diketone-linked dimer consisting of two 4-cyanobiphenyl units connected by a heptane-1,7-dione spacer, which introduces carbonyl functionality into the flexible bridge.

An organic molecule comprising a distyrylbenzene core where the terminal aromatic rings bear branched 2-octyldodecyl alkoxy substituents at the 2 and 5 positions, exhibiting a low temperature solid-to-fluid transformation.

This compound is a dendritic intermediate synthesized via the alkylation of 5-bromobenzene-1,3-diol. The reaction employs two equivalents of BrC6CN to generate the final product. The structure features a central bromobenzene core substituted at the 1 and 3 positions.
A polypyrrolidone polymer composed of repeating 4-aminobutyric acid units.

A 2:1 supramolecular co-crystal composed of 4-ethoxybenzoic acid and 4,4'-bipyridyl. The structure consists of a linear hydrogen-bonded trimer where two acid molecules coordinate to the nitrogen atoms of the central bipyridyl base through intermolecular interactions, with the benzoic acid moiety bearing an ethoxy group at the para position.
A pyridine derivative substituted with a methyl group, a phenolic hydroxyl, and two hydroxymethyl groups, functioning as an essential vitamin cofactor.
A small organic molecule consisting of an acetamide core substituted with an iodine atom on the alpha carbon, often used as an alkylating agent.

The molecule is based on a fused polycyclic dibenzo[a,c]phenazine core, which consists of a phenazine-type diazine unit fused to two benzene rings. This aromatic framework is substituted at the 2, 3, 6, and 7 positions with hexyloxy groups, forming aryl–O–(CH2)5–CH3 ether linkages. Additionally, the 11-position of the core features a carboxyl substituent present as a methyl ester (aryl–C(=O)–OCH3).
A C2-symmetric bis-acetylenic molecule consisting of two N-(4-ethynylbenzoyl)-L-valine units linked via a decamethylene diester spacer.

A gold(III) complex featuring a 2,6-bis(4-dodecyloxyphenyl)pyridine ligand coordinated to the metal center, alongside a phenylacetylide ligand substituted at the 3 and 4 positions with 1H,1H,2H,2H-perfluorodecyloxy chains.

c-DOPA(12) • NaBF4 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

(S, S)-3 is an aromatic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, while ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
An aromatic polyester synthesized from 1,3-propanediol and terephthalic acid.
A five-membered cyclic anhydride derivative of glutamic acid protected at the gamma-carboxyl position with a benzyl ester, used as a monomer for ring-opening polymerization.

This symmetric molecule features a central squaramide core (a four-membered ring diamide) linked to two outer phenyl rings via flexible ethylene spacers. Each of the two terminal phenyl rings is substituted with three long dodecyloxy chains at the 3, 4, and 5 positions, enabling intermolecular hydrogen bonding through the central amide groups.

phase_transition_behavior: Heating: Cr 135.4 N 154.0 I. Cooling: Cr 116.6 NTB 121 (POM) N 151.5 I.
description: The molecule is a symmetric trimer centered on a 4,4′-disubstituted biphenyl core. Extending from each para position of this central core is an undecyloxy spacer (–O–(CH2)11–). These spacers terminate in a thioether linkage (–S–) connecting to a terminal biphenyl unit. Each of the two terminal biphenyl units is substituted at the para position with a nitrile group (–C≡N), resulting in two identical 4-cyanobiphenyl thioether end groups flanking the central structure.
A cyanide-bridged {Fe6Co7} cluster complex containing N-hexadecyl-2,2'-dipyridylamine ligands. It displays a columnar hexagonal structure characterized by wide-angle X-ray scattering.
A surfactant molecule synthesized from D-xylose and diethylene glycol monododecyl ether, featuring a dodecyl alkyl chain linked to a xyloside group via a dioxyethylene spacer.

Xylitol is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A fluorinated molecule consisting of three phenyl rings linked by ester bonds. It contains a terminal 3-fluoro-4-nitrophenyl group and a 2,4-dimethoxybenzoyl moiety.

An ethanolamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of oleic acid with the amino group of ethanolamine. The structure comprises a long-chain monounsaturated fatty acyl tail (C18:1) linked via an amide bond to a 2-hydroxyethyl group.

A trimeric molecule constructed around a central 1,2,4-substituted benzene core. This core is connected to three peripheral triphenylene units via propyl ether linkages. Each of the three triphenylene moieties is further substituted with five pentyloxy chains at the 3, 6, 7, 10, and 11 positions.

phase_transition_behavior: From Table 1 (compound 2b, ethyl ester): Cr 64.3 → Colh 210.8 → I (additional listed value: 209.5). Clearing point taken as the Colh→I transition on heating: 210.8 °C.
description: The molecule comprises a rigid, fused polycyclic dibenzo[a,c]phenazine core incorporating a phenazine-type diazine unit with two nitrogen atoms. Four hexyloxy substituents are attached to the aromatic framework at the 2,3,6,7-positions via aryl–O–alkyl ether linkages, with each substituent consisting of a linear six-carbon chain bound through an oxygen atom. At the 11-position, the aromatic core bears a carboxylate group esterified as an ethyl ester (aryl–C(=O)–O–CH2CH3).
An aliphatic polyamide synthesized from 1,6-hexanediamine and tridecanedioic acid, featuring amide linkages separated by methylene segments.
An aliphatic polyester derived from the reaction of 1,4-butanediol and glutaric acid, featuring a flexible hydrocarbon chain with repeating ester groups.
A disk-shaped molecule comprising a tristriazolotriazine core substituted with three 4-(2-hexyloctyloxy)phenyl groups.

A rigid, star-shaped heteroaromatic molecule consisting of a central tristriazolotriazine core substituted with three phenyl rings. It is synthesized via the cyclocondensation of 5-phenyltetrazole with cyanuric chloride.

phase_transition_behavior: From Table 1 (n = 10): heating shows a direct Cr → I transition at 184.8 °C (no N–I transition reported on heating). Upon cooling: I → N at 176.2 °C (TIN), crystallization at 150.7 °C (TCr), and a monotropic SmA phase was observed by POM at 146 °C (TNS, footnote a). The clearing point is therefore taken as TIN = 176.2 °C.
description: This molecule is a symmetric trimer constructed around a central 4,4′-biphenyl core. Both para positions of this central core are substituted with identical alkoxy chains, specifically decyloxy groups (–O–(CH2)10–). Each of these decamethylene spacers is linked at its terminal end via a thioether bond (–S–) to an outer 4,4′-biphenyl unit. Each of these two terminal biphenyl groups is substituted at the para position relative to the sulfur linkage with a nitrile (–C≡N) group. The overall structure consists of a central biphenyl unit connected by two flexible ether-thioether alkyl chains to two terminal cyanobiphenyl moieties.
The molecule consists of a [1]benzothieno[3,2-b][1]benzothiophene (BTBT) core substituted at the 2-position with a 4-methylphenyl group and at the 7-position with an undecyl chain.

A regioregular conjugated polymer featuring a thiophene backbone substituted with a six-carbon alkyl chain at the 3-position. This lipophilic side chain enhances solubility in organic solvents, facilitating solution processing for electronic devices.

NPG-d6+2 is an aromatic organic scaffold with a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A pyridinium-functionalized amino acid derivative composed of an L-isoleucine core N-acylated with an isonicotinoyl group, isolated as the hydrochloride salt.
A chiral surfactant composed of a palmitic acid tail linked via an amide bond to an L-phenylalanine headgroup.
Rigid, high-aspect-ratio rod-like crystalline particles composed of beta-1,4-linked D-glucose polymer chains, featuring surface carboxyl functional groups.
Layered CdCl2-OTAB precursor complex

A fluorinated homopolymer synthesized via RAFT polymerization. The structure consists of a polyacrylate backbone with pendant perfluorooctylethyl chains containing a perfluorinated segment and an ethyl spacer.

A three-ring organic molecule consisting of a central 3-methoxyphenyl ring connected via an azomethine linkage to a 4-(hexyloxy)phenyl group on one side and attached via an ester linkage to a 4-methylbenzoate group on the other.

A lipidated peptide conjugate consisting of a hexadecanoyl chain attached to the N-terminus of the pentapeptide sequence Lys-Thr-Thr-beta-Ala-His, featuring an alkyl tail and a peptide headgroup containing amine, hydroxyl, imidazole, and carboxylic acid functionalities.

phase_transition_behavior: From Table 1 (n = 3; CBS3OBO3SCB): heating shows Cr → I at 186.4 °C (no N–I transition reported on heating). On cooling, a monotropic N phase is observed with I → N at 142 °C (POM), followed by crystallization at 144.8 °C.
description: This molecule is a symmetric trimer centered on a 4,4′-biphenyl core. The central biphenyl unit is substituted at both para positions (4 and 4′) with alkoxy groups. Each oxygen atom is attached to a propyl spacer (–CH2–CH2–CH2–), which in turn connects to a sulfur atom via a thioether linkage. Each sulfur atom is bonded to the 4′-position of a terminal 4-cyanobiphenyl unit, resulting in two outer biphenyl systems that each carry a nitrile group (–C≡N) at the para position. The overall structure consists of a central biphenyl ring system linked via two propoxy-thioether chains to two terminal cyanobiphenyl groups.
Rod-like organic nanoparticles featuring a twisted crystalline structure and abundant surface hydroxyl groups, capable of self-assembling into ordered helical domains in aqueous suspensions.

A biodegradable synthetic polyester produced by the ring-opening polymerization of epsilon-caprolactone. It is a semicrystalline material with a linear aliphatic chain structure, widely used in composites and biomedical applications.

4-((4-nitrophenoxy)carbonyl)phenyl 2-(hexyloxy)-4-methoxybenzoate is an aromatic diester with a rigid core and a flexible hexyloxy chain. It features nitro and methoxy substituents attached to the phenyl rings. The molecule is characterized by ester linkages and extended conjugation.

A T-shaped organic molecule featuring a benzodifuran core substituted with butyl esters and a twisted 4-nitrophenyl group. It is synthesized via the condensation of a diamino-benzodifuran derivative with 2-hydroxybenzaldehyde. The structure contains two Schiff base units with intramolecular hydrogen bonds between the phenolic hydroxyls and imine nitrogens, forming rigid half-salen moieties that restrict rotation and enable red fluorescence.
A substituted benzoic acid derivative featuring a central imine linkage connecting a benzoic acid moiety to a 4-hexyloxyphenyl group.

phase_transition_behavior: Figure captions indicate a transition near 78 °C (caption notes a threshold temperature of 78 °C; stripe images are described as close to the transition just below 77.4 °C).
description: The molecule consists of two benzene rings linked by an ester group. The acid-derived portion of the ester is a benzoate ring substituted at the 3-position with a but-3-enyl group, which is a four-carbon chain terminating in a carbon-carbon double bond. The alcohol-derived portion is a phenyl ring substituted at the 4-position with a methoxy group.

A polymerizable monomer consisting of a 2,5-dibromobenzoate group linked via a decamethylene spacer to a rigid core structure. This core comprises a pyrimidine ring connected to a fluorophenyl ring, which is further substituted with a dodecyloxy chain.
A bromine-containing diester derived from 4-bromo-2-methoxybenzoic acid and 4-nitrophenyl 4-hydroxybenzoate. It possesses a terminal aryl ring substituted with a methoxy group and a bromine atom.
A symmetric bis-ether derivative in which two 4'-cyanobiphenyl-4-yl groups are linked via their oxygen atoms to the 1- and 5-positions of a central pentane chain.
A chiral molecule comprising an adenine moiety linked to a triphenylamine core via an (S)-2-methylpropyl spacer, with the triphenylamine unit substituted by two dodecyloxy side chains.
Monomer prepared from 3-(3′-thienyl)propyl toluene-p-sulfonate and (S)-2-phenylbutanol.

A biologically active catecholamine consisting of a benzene ring substituted with two hydroxyl groups at the 3 and 4 positions, and an ethylamine side chain. It functions as a key neurotransmitter and is synthesized in the body from L-DOPA.
A Janus molecule comprising a cholesteryl unit and a disaccharide moiety linked by a flexible spacer, featuring a lateral decyl chain attached to the sugar ring via a carbamate linkage.

An organic compound comprising a rigid aromatic core of three benzene rings linked by ester groups. The structure features a lateral heptyloxy chain and a methoxy group on one terminal benzene ring, while the opposite terminus consists of a 3-fluoro-4-nitrophenyl moiety.

phase_transition_behavior: Figure 4 caption indicates DSC heating and cooling curves were recorded for R2 (at a stated scan rate). Figure 5 caption indicates polarized optical micrographs were taken for R2 between treated/untreated glass substrate pairs at a specified observation temperature.
description: The molecule consists of a central cyclohexane ring substituted at the 1 and 4 positions in a trans configuration. One substituent on the cyclohexane ring is an n-propyl chain, while the other is a phenyl group. This phenyl ring is further substituted at the para position relative to the cyclohexyl attachment with an ethoxy group (–O–CH2–CH3), resulting in a 1,4-disubstituted benzene ring linked to the cyclohexane core.

The molecule consists of a central p-phenylene ring connected to two 4-glycidyloxybenzylidene groups via imine linkages at the para positions. The structure terminates at both ends with glycidyl ether functional groups.

A highly stable conducting polymer based on a bicyclic monomer where a thiophene ring is fused to a dioxane-like ring. It is characterized by an ethylenedioxy substituent at the 3 and 4 positions and is often used in conjunction with sulfonate counterions to form conductive films.

A heteroaromatic dicarboxylic acid consisting of a furan ring substituted at the 2 and 5 positions with carboxylic acid groups. It is synthesized through the base-free aerobic oxidation of 5-hydroxymethylfurfural, often utilizing functionalized platinum nanoparticles on carbon nanotubes as a catalyst.
A metabolite of tryptophan characterized by an aromatic ring substituted with an amine and a ketone group. It is a central intermediate in the major catabolic pathway of tryptophan.
This compound is an organic salt comprising a protonated pyrazole ring and a tetrafluoroborate anion. It is synthesized for analysis of its thermal stability and caloric characteristics.
An ester of cinnamic acid and a glycol ether. It acts as a UVB absorber and is typically found as a viscous oil.
The iodide salt of a dodecyloxyphenyl-substituted tetramethylguanidinium cation. Formed by treating the chloride precursor with potassium iodide.

An organic star-shaped molecule featuring a central tris([1,2,4]triazolo)[1,5-a:1',5'-c:1'',5''-e][1,3,5]triazine core substituted at the 2, 5, and 9 positions with three 4-(2-decyldodecyloxy)phenyl groups.

A semi-synthetic polysaccharide derivative featuring a cellulose backbone in which the hydroxyl groups are substituted with propionyl ester moieties. This modification is achieved through the esterification of hydroxypropyl cellulose with propionic anhydride. The resulting structure comprises a flexible polymer chain characterized by the presence of both hydroxypropyl ether and propionyl ester functional groups attached to the anhydroglucose units.
An ionic salt consisting of a pyrazolium cation and a hydrogensulfate anion. It is studied for its thermal properties, specifically its heat of fusion and behavior for energy storage.

A molecule comprising a central 1-acetyl-4,5-dihydro-1H-pyrazole ring substituted at the 3-position with a 4-methoxyphenyl group and at the 5-position with a phenyl ring. This phenyl ring is part of an azobenzene system, linked via a diazenyl group to a second phenyl ring. The second phenyl ring of the azobenzene moiety is esterified at the para position with 4-(decyloxy)benzoic acid, featuring a ten-carbon alkyl chain.
An oligomer consisting of two fluorene units connected in a linear fashion and terminated with a nitrile group.
A simple aliphatic polyester derived from glycolic acid.
A covalently crosslinked network formed by the reaction of a biphenyl diepoxide with a dicarboxylic acid featuring an internal disulfide linkage.
Compound 19[BF4] (1,3-didodecylimidazolium tetrafluoroborate) consists of an imidazolium core substituted with two long dodecyl side-chain alkyl groups.

A tetracyclic triterpenoid sapogenin of the dammarane type, consisting of a steroidal core with a hydroxylated aliphatic side chain. It is produced by the enzymatic hydrolysis of sugar moieties from specific plant glycosides found in ginseng.

(S, S)-6 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It contains heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Substituent patterns and terminal groups define the overall shape, polarity, and steric bulk.

An ethyl benzoate derivative featuring a hydroxyl group and a fluorosulfonyloxy moiety on the aromatic ring. This solid compound serves as a mono-functionalized intermediate for SuFEx polymerization monomers.

A diester phospholipid in which a glycerol backbone is esterified at the 1- and 2-positions by two polyunsaturated docosapentaenoyl chains, while the 3-position is linked to a phosphoinositol headgroup.
Oxidized monomethoxy poly(ethylene glycol) (mPEG) with terminal carboxyl groups, prepared via TEMPO oxidation. Used as a grafting agent.
An unsymmetrical rod-shaped organic molecule comprising a central phenyl ring bearing a lateral methoxy group, connected to a 4-hexyloxyphenyl imine unit and a 4-methoxybenzoate ester unit.
A tri-aromatic ester compound comprising a central hydroquinone-derived ester linkage, substituted with a lateral heptyloxy chain and a terminal nitrophenyl group.

A spin-labeled fatty acid where a stable doxyl radical ring is attached to the 16th carbon of the stearic acid chain. It serves as a reporter for the dynamics and fluidity of the deep hydrophobic regions in self-assembled structures.

A heterocyclic chromophore featuring a 1-methylimidazole ring. It carries 4-(dimethylamino)phenyl substituents and a 4-nitrophenyl group connected by a conjugated buta-1,3-dienyl linker at the 2-position.
Synthesized from 1,4-phenylenediamine, cinnamaldehyde, and benzaldehyde. It comprises a central benzene ring linked by Schiff base units to a styryl group and a phenyl group.
A beta-hydroxy acid consisting of a benzene ring substituted with adjacent hydroxyl and carboxyl groups.
An unnatural amino acid enantiomer consisting of glycine substituted with a phenyl group.
An organic molecule featuring a tris([1,2,4]triazolo)[1,5-a:1',5'-c:1'',5''-e][1,3,5]triazine core substituted at the 2, 5, and 9 positions with three 3,4-ditetradecyloxyphenyl groups.

c-DOPA(16) • NaBF4 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A triphenylene derivative featuring a central aromatic core substituted with five pentyloxy chains at positions 3, 6, 7, 10, and 11, and a single propargyl ether group at position 2.
A vinyl polymer synthesized from 4-vinylpyridine. The structure contains pyridine rings attached to a hydrocarbon backbone, which can act as a weak base or be quaternized to form polyelectrolytes.

An organometallic gold(III) complex coordinated by a tridentate [2,6-bis(3,4-bis(dodecyloxy)phenyl)pyridine] pincer ligand and a monodentate 3,4-bis(1H,1H,2H,2H-perfluorodecyloxy)phenylacetylide ligand.

NPG-d2 features a rigid aromatic core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The scaffold includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A photochromic diarylethene derivative (referred to as DBTEO) used in dual-color fluorescent nanoparticles.
Alternative carbon source for CNT preparation; also used as a solvent (droplets) for shrinking/densifying CNT yarns in vertical-array spinning.
An organosulfate salt consisting of a linear twelve-carbon alkyl chain attached to a sulfate group, counterbalanced by a sodium cation.

A phosphatidylethanolamine molecule based on a glycerol backbone, esterified at the sn-1 position with a saturated hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) chain and at the sn-2 position with a monounsaturated (9Z)-octadecenoyl (oleoyl) chain, with the sn-3 position linked to a phosphoethanolamine group.

A bicyclo[1.1.1]pentane derivative substituted with a carboxylic acid and a methyl ester at the bridgehead positions. It serves as a starting material for the synthesis of iodinated bicyclic compounds and exhibits a distinct melting endotherm.

Produced by the glycosylation of diethylene glycol monooctyl ether with a protected xylose donor. This amphiphilic compound contains an octyl chain, a polyethylene glycol-like spacer, and a polar carbohydrate head group.
Natural lipophilic antioxidant loaded into monoolein aqueous dispersions; influences the morphology of the lipid nanostructures.
A pentaglycerol ester surfactant containing a saturated twelve-carbon alkyl chain.
A sterically hindered aluminum(III) complex bearing three 1,3-di-tert-butyltriazenide ligands. It is analyzed for its volatility and thermal decomposition mechanism.

c-DOPA(14) • KPF6 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A biodegradable aliphatic polyester derived from epsilon-caprolactone.

A sterol ester resulting from the formal condensation of the 3-hydroxy group of cholesterol with the carboxy group of octadecanoic acid. It consists of a tetracyclic steroid core linked via an ester bond to a long, saturated 18-carbon alkyl chain.

Bn6 is an aromatic scaffold with a rigid core, linkers, and flexible side chains. It includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A five-membered cyclic imide derivative substituted with a hydroxyl group on the nitrogen atom, used in bioconjugation chemistry.
Alternative carbon source mentioned for the preparation of CNTs by the CVD method.
A water-soluble polyelectrolyte end-functionalized with a hydrophobic steroidal group, forming micelles in aqueous solution.

A 4,5-dicyanoimidazole derivative synthesized by diazotization and azo coupling. The molecule comprises an imidazole ring substituted with two cyano groups and linked via an azo bond to a phenyl ring bearing a bis(2-hydroxyethyl)amino group.

A steroid derivative comprising a tetracyclic hydrocarbon core linked to a long-chain unsaturated aliphatic group via a carbonate ester. The molecule features a rigid chiral backbone and a flexible oleyl tail containing a cis-double bond.

DIO is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

The sodium salt of a xanthene-based dye, comprising a fused tricyclic system linked to a benzene ring with carboxylate functionality. This water-soluble compound is utilized for its intense green fluorescence.
A benzophenone derivative substituted with hydroxyl and methoxy groups. It is utilized to protect materials and skin from the damaging effects of UV light.
A cadmium-based zeolitic imidazolate framework synthesized mechanochemically from cadmium oxide and imidazole. It forms a glass upon quenching from the fluid state.
A hexadecanoic acid ester of decaglycerol.
A conjugated polymer prone to inter-chain aggregation in certain solvents, typically containing fluorinated aromatic units.
A bacterial copolymer containing 3-hydroxybutyrate and 3-hydroxyvalerate segments.
A small aromatic molecule consisting of a benzene ring substituted with an amino group and a carboxylic acid. It is a known UVB absorber and biological intermediate.

A phospholipid conjugate characterized by a hexadecanoyl chain attached at the sn-1 position and a 4-methoxybenzoyl group at the sn-2 position of the glycerol backbone, linked to a polar phosphocholine headgroup.
A dipeptide conjugate comprising L-methionine and L-serine residues, N-acylated with a 4-ethynylbenzoyl moiety and terminated with a phenyl ester.

Nt1 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A mono-unsaturated organic ester comprising a linear saturated C22 alcohol component and a C18 fatty acid component with a single cis-double bond.
A bright yellow diarylheptanoid pigment. The molecule comprises two ferulic acid residues linked by a methylene bridge and exists in equilibrium between keto and enol forms.

A conjugated polymer possessing a polydiacetylene backbone with phenyl side groups. It is prepared by photo-induced polymerization of 1,4-diphenylbutadiyne monomers solubilized within a surfactant-based soft template. The material forms nanofibrous structures and demonstrates visible-light responsiveness.

Rigid, rod-like nanoparticles possessing a high aspect ratio and a stiff crystalline structure derived from cellulose. The surface features sulfate ester groups resulting from acid hydrolysis, rendering the whiskers hydrophilic. These particles form stable colloidal suspensions due to electrostatic repulsion between the surface charges.

A trisubstituted 1-methylimidazole derivative synthesized via Debus–Radziszewski condensation. It features two electron-donating 4-(dimethylamino)phenyl groups at the 4 and 5 positions and an electron-withdrawing 4-nitrophenyl group at the 2 position, forming a donor-pi-acceptor system.
A camphor derivative containing a benzylidene bridge and sulfonic acid groups. It is water-soluble and effective at absorbing UVA rays.
A small aliphatic diol consisting of a propane chain with two hydroxyl groups. It is commonly employed as a solvent, viscosity modifier, and humectant in pharmaceutical formulations.
A small molecule semiconductor with a silolo[3,2-b:4,5-b']dithiophene core, substituted with ethylhexyl groups and flanked by fluorinated benzothiadiazole and hexyl-bithiophene units.
A heterocyclic pyrone derivative substituted with two carboxylic acid groups.
A planar aromatic trialdehyde featuring formyl groups at the 1, 3, and 5 positions of a benzene ring.
A fully deuterated isotopologue of 4'-pentyl-4-biphenylcarbonitrile, in which all hydrogen atoms on the pentyl chain and the biphenyl core have been replaced by deuterium.
The compound is tetra(n-pentyl) perylene-3,4,9,10-tetracarboxylate, which consists of a perylene-3,4,9,10-tetracarboxylate core substituted with four n-pentyl alkyl chains.

A chlorinated ester compound comprising a 4-chloro-2-methoxyphenyl group linked to a 4-nitrophenyl 4-oxybenzoate backbone. The structure includes a chlorine atom and a methoxy group on the terminal ring.
A conjugated polymer comprising bithiophene repeating units substituted with dodecyl alkyl chains, noted for compact pi-pi stacking.
A glycoside formed by the conjugation of salicylic acid with a glucose molecule.
A diester in which a central 2-chlorobenzene-1,4-diol core is substituted at the 1 and 4 positions by 4-(pent-4-en-1-yloxy)benzoyl groups.

description: A bio-based polyester synthesized from 2,5-furandicarboxylic acid and 1,5-pentanediol. It features a furan aromatic ring linked to a five-carbon aliphatic chain, displaying slow crystallization kinetics and forming a semicrystalline structure upon long-term storage.

A D-lysine derivative in which a hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) chain is attached to the alpha-amino group, while the epsilon-amino group remains free. The structure consists of a hydrophobic hexadecyl tail linked via an amide bond to the chiral amino acid core, which terminates in a primary amine and a carboxylic acid or amide functionality.

A nitrogen-containing heterocyclic polymer synthesized via oxidation of five-membered aromatic rings. It features a conjugated backbone capable of supporting charge carriers and is often prepared using oxidative polymerization with ferric salts.

description: 3-Acetoxybenzoic acid consists of a single benzene ring bearing two substituents: a carboxylic acid group directly attached to the ring (–C(=O)OH) and an acetoxy group (–O–C(=O)CH3) attached through an aromatic oxygen (an aryl ester). The acetoxy substituent is located meta to the carboxylic acid on the aromatic ring. It can be synthesized by O-acetylation of 3-hydroxybenzoic acid using acetic anhydride (commonly in an aromatic solvent under reflux), converting the phenolic –OH into the acetate ester while leaving the carboxylic acid functionality intact.

A polysaccharide derivative of cellulose in which some of the hydroxyl groups on the repeating glucose units have been etherified with hydroxypropyl groups. The polymer consists of a linear backbone of $\beta$-(1$\rightarrow$4)-linked D-glucose units, with hydroxypropyl substituents attached via ether linkages. Due to intramolecular hydrogen bonding, the backbone maintains a rigid, rod-like conformation.
A pi-shaped molecule featuring a p-terphenyl core substituted with two lateral dodecyloxy chains at the 2' and 3' positions and glycerol units at the 4 and 4'' positions.

A branched-chain aliphatic triol identified as 3,7,11,15-tetramethyl-1,2,3-hexadecanetriol. The molecule consists of a saturated, hydrophobic phytanyl backbone (an isoprenoid-type tail) attached to a polar headgroup containing three hydroxyl moieties, devoid of ester bonds.

A naphthalene-based fluorescent dye substituted with an electron-donating dimethylamino group and a hydrophobic dodecanoyl ketone tail. It is used as a probe to sense polarity changes in organic environments.
Monomer synthesized from (S)-(+)-1-bromo-2-methyloctyl Grignard reagent.
A high-performance semi-aromatic polyamide made from 1,9-nonanediamine and terephthalic acid.
An organic salt comprising a 1-octyl-3-methylimidazolium cation and a chloride anion, characterized by an eight-carbon alkyl tail.

A conjugated organic polymer featuring an ethylenedioxythiophene repeat unit. It is synthesized via chemical oxidative polymerization of the corresponding monomer using iron(III) chloride as an oxidant within a surfactant-stabilized soft template. The resulting material forms nanostructures such as spindles or hollow capsules and exhibits a narrow band gap with absorption in the visible and near-infrared regions.
A fused-ring organic molecule comprising a benzothieno[3,2-b]benzothiophene core with tert-butyl substituents, commonly used in field-effect transistors.

A benzonitrile derivative bearing a hydroxyl group and a fluorosulfonyloxy group. This solid intermediate is used in the synthesis of cyano-functionalized monomers for sulfur-fluoride exchange chemistry.
An asymmetric photochromic dye composed of a naphthalene ring linked to a phenyl ring through a diazenyl group. The extended aromatic system influences its optical absorption.

The molecule consists of a triphenylene aromatic core substituted at the 3, 6, 7, 10, and 11 positions with five pentyloxy groups, and at the 2-position with a single 10-undecynyloxy chain containing a terminal alkyne.
A rigid heteroaromatic molecule containing a pyromellitic diimide core flanked by two isophthalic acid moieties, capable of forming conductive hydrogels.

A synthesized pyrazoline derivative featuring a 1-acetyl-4,5-dihydro-1H-pyrazole core, substituted with a 4-methoxyphenyl group at the 3-position and an azobenzene moiety with an octyloxy tail at the 5-position. Prepared via cyclization of the corresponding chalcone precursor with hydrazine and acetic acid.

Polysaccharide nanorods characterized by the absence of sulfate half-ester groups and the presence of carboxyl functionalities introduced via C6 oxidation. These particles exhibit a modified surface charge density relative to the fully sulfated analog.
Synthesized via polyaddition of dihydrocyclotetrasiloxanes with divinylcyclotetrasiloxanes.
A polymer synthesized from 1,4-butanediol and dodecanedioic acid, characterized by long aliphatic chains separating the ester linkages.
A derivative of the polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon pyrene, functionalized with a single hydroxyl group at the 1-position, often used as a polarity-sensitive fluorescent probe.
A dihydroxy-substituted benzophenone. It is used as an ultraviolet stabilizer to prevent photodegradation in polymers and cosmetics.
A sulfonated benzophenone derivative that is water-soluble. It is widely used in sunscreens and personal care products to filter ultraviolet radiation.

A monoacylglycerol lipid comprising a glycerol headgroup esterified at the sn-1 position with (Z)-heptadec-7-enoic acid. The molecule features a 17-carbon fatty acyl chain with a cis-alkene group positioned seven carbons from the carbonyl ester linkage.

A symmetric dicationic molecule comprising two decyl-substituted imidazolium cores linked by an ethylene chain, with tetrafluoroborate counterions. Prepared by quaternizing 1-decylimidazole with 1,2-dibromoethane and exchanging the anion.

A pi-shaped molecule featuring a p-terphenyl core substituted with two lateral decyloxy chains at the 2' and 3' positions and glycerol units at the 4 and 4'' positions. The compound is synthesized via Suzuki cross-coupling of a 1,2-bis(decyloxy)-3,6-diiodobenzene intermediate with a boronic acid derivative containing a protected glycerol moiety, followed by acidic deprotection.

A chemical compound consisting of a 4-nitrophenyl 4-hydroxybenzoate core esterified with 2-methoxy-4-methylbenzoic acid. The molecule features a methyl and a methoxy substituent on the terminal benzene ring.

A star-shaped organic molecule comprising a tetraphenylethene core where each of the four phenyl rings is para-substituted with a bulky cholesterol unit linked via a carbonate ester. Synthesized from 1,1,2,2-tetrakis(4-hydroxyphenyl)ethylene and cholesteryl chloroformate, this compound features a rigid, propeller-like architecture with chiral steroid appendages capable of undergoing reversible photocyclization.

A tetracyclic sterol molecule featuring a fused four-ring core, a hydroxyl group at the C-3 position, and a hydrocarbon side chain. It functions as a critical structural component in animal cell membranes, modulating fluidity, and acts as a biosynthetic precursor for steroid hormones and bile acids.
A low-corrosive acid solvent used to disperse CNTs for assembly in solution spinning.
A non-ionic surfactant comprising a maltose disaccharide polar head group linked to a branched C15 hexahydrofarnesyl hydrophobic chain.
A fluorinated tri-aryl ester featuring a lateral propoxy chain and terminating in a 3-fluoro-4-nitrophenyl group.

A heteroaromatic organic compound consisting of a furan ring substituted with formyl and hydroxymethyl functional groups. It is produced by the dehydration of sugars and acts as a platform for creating renewable fuels and polyesters.
A simple phenolic ketone extracted from the root bark of Paeonia suffruticosa. The molecule consists of an acetophenone scaffold substituted with methoxy and hydroxy groups.
An organic molecule comprising three benzene rings linked by ester groups, featuring a lateral octyloxy chain and a terminal nitro group.
Optically active phosphine oxide based monothiophene.
