description: A crystalline complex consisting of a 2:1 ratio of 4-n-butoxybenzoic acid to 4,4'-bipyridyl, crystallized from ethanol. The supramolecular architecture is established by hydrogen bonding between the carboxylic acid donors and the pyridyl nitrogen acceptors. The molecular structure of the acid component includes a linear butoxy chain attached to the aromatic ring.

phase_transition_behavior: Clearing point for YHD1 is not provided in any TABLE or FIGURE CAPTION in the supplied content; no phase sequence for YHD1 is tabulated/captioned to infer T_NI or T_Iso.
description:
Molecular structure: YHD1 is a symmetric croconium (croconaine-type) dye built around a five-membered oxygen-rich croconate core that is conjugated to two thiophene rings. Each thiophene unit is further substituted with a piperidine ring through the piperidine nitrogen (an N–C(aryl/heteroaryl) linkage), and each piperidine bears a 4-carboxylate group esterified as a methyl ester.

Synthesis: The molecule is prepared by first forming an N-substituted isonipecotate intermediate in which a thiophene-derived nucleophile is coupled to methyl isonipecotate to give an N-(thiophenyl) piperidine-4-carboxylate ester (intermediate 6). Two equivalents of this thiophene–piperidine intermediate are then condensed with croconic acid under dehydrating reflux conditions to assemble the conjugated bis(thiophene)-substituted croconium core, yielding YHD1.

A cellulose derivative in which the hydroxyl groups of hydroxypropyl cellulose have been esterified with propionyl chloride. This polymeric material consists of a cellulose backbone modified with both hydroxypropyl ether and propionate ester functional groups.
A triglycerol-based non-ionic surfactant esterified with a single dodecanoyl group.

A jelly-like salt formed from 1-dodecylpyridinium chloride and iron(III) bromide. The structure incorporates a mixed-halide ferrate anion, resulting in a material that lacks crystallinity at ambient conditions.
Racemic monomer formed by reaction of 3-bromothiophene with hexan-3-ylzinc chloride.
A dicationic amphiphile derived from 3-pentadecylphenol. The synthesis involves linking the phenolic tail via a butenyl spacer to a diazabicyclo[2.2.2]octane core which bears a hexyl chain.

This compound is a polyfluorinated biphenyl carboxylate ester. It comprises a 4'-ethyl-2',3,5,6'-tetrafluorobiphenyl moiety esterified with 4-cyano-3,5-difluorophenol. The rigid aromatic framework bears multiple fluorine atoms, a terminal ethyl group, and a polar cyano group.

A molecule comprising a 1-acetyl-4,5-dihydro-1H-pyrazole core substituted at the 3-position with a 4-methoxyphenyl group and at the 5-position with a phenyl ring. This phenyl ring is connected via a diazenyl (azo) linkage to a second phenyl ring, forming an azobenzene unit. The second phenyl ring of the azobenzene moiety is esterified with a 4-(tetradecyloxy)benzoic acid group, featuring a long-chain tetradecyloxy tail.

An aliphatic-aromatic polymer prepared by reacting dimethyl-2,5-thiophenedicarboxylate with 1,5-pentanediol in the presence of titanium catalysts. Its repeating unit consists of a 2,5-disubstituted thiophene core connected to a pentamethylene chain.

A soluble pentacene derivative functionalized with bulky silylethynyl groups at the 6 and 13 positions to disrupt face-to-face pi-stacking and improve solubility. The bulky groups induce a brick-work packing motif in the solid state, beneficial for charge transport.
A phosphorylated seven-carbon monosaccharide derivative acting as a key intermediate in the shikimate pathway.

A fully acetylated glucose molecule with an acetyl group at the anomeric position. Lacking the linear dipolar azide or isothiocyanate functionality, it serves as a non-assembling reference compound in structural studies.

A hexa-substituted phosphazene compound featuring a cyclotriphosphazene (P3N3) core with six identical radiating substituents. Each substituent arm contains an azomethine linkage connecting to a benzamide moiety, which is further substituted with a terminal decyloxy chain.

An amphiphilic molecule comprising a cholesterol unit linked via a butyl spacer to an acetamide group, which is further attached to a disaccharide moiety (specifically a maltose derivative). This disaccharide core features a lateral hexadecyl chain attached at the 2-position of one glucose unit via a carbamate linkage, creating a structure with distinct hydrophilic sugar and hydrophobic steroid/alkyl domains.
A perylene core substituted with four n-heptyl ester groups at the 3, 4, 9, and 10 positions.

A dinitrile derivative comprising a 1,2-dicyanobenzene core substituted at the 4-position with a 4-tritylphenoxy group. The molecule features a bulky triphenylmethyl moiety linked via an ether bridge to the phthalonitrile ring. It serves as a precursor for the synthesis of soluble metallophthalocyanine complexes.

A linear oligomer synthesized from the reaction of n-butylamine with a diacrylate monomer featuring a phenyl benzoate core. The repeating unit consists of a central phenyl benzoate moiety flanked by hexyloxy chains, which are connected via ester linkages to the polymer backbone formed by the addition of the amine to the acrylate groups. The structure is characterized by alternating rigid aromatic ester segments and flexible alkyl spacers with amine linkages, lacking any lateral substituents on the aromatic core.

A meta-substituted aromatic compound consisting of a nitrobenzene ring linked to a pentafluorophenyl group through a perfluorinated ethyl spacer. Synthesized using a controllable double fluorocarbon insertion strategy.

An organic molecule featuring a linear core of three phenyl rings connected by ester linkages. The structure includes a benzoyl fragment substituted with a hexyloxy side chain and a methoxy group, while the opposite end of the molecule is terminated by a nitro group.
An organosilane ammonium salt featuring a propylammonium core substituted with two methyl groups, a long-chain octadecyl group, and a trimethoxysilyl moiety, balanced by a chloride counterion.

A seven-membered fluorinated heterocycle containing a 1,2-oxazepine framework with an oxygen-nitrogen linkage. Prepared through ring-closing metathesis using a ruthenium-based catalyst, the structure is characterized by a fluorine substituent located on the cyclic double bond.
A salicylic acid ester used as a solvent and photostabilizer. It is structurally similar to octisalate but utilizes butyloctanol in its esterification.

A solution-processable n-type organic semiconductor molecule based on a rigid indeno[1,2-b]fluorene core. It is functionalized with electron-withdrawing dicyanovinylene groups at the bridgehead positions and 3-octylthiophene moieties at the 2 and 8 positions. The compound is synthesized via Stille coupling of a dibrominated dione intermediate followed by Knoevenagel condensation.

c-DOPA(16) • KPF6 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A sulfurimidoyl difluoride derivative substituted with a 4-nitrophenyl group. It is employed as an initiator for the chain-growth SuFEx polymerization of aryl fluorosulfates.

phase_transition_behavior: On cooling, the reported sequence for compound 1/16 is: Iso → SmA (at ~140 °C) → SmCS (at 125 °C) → SmCSPFhel (at 110 °C) → SmCPA (below 90 °C).
description: The molecule is constructed around a central 1,3-disubstituted benzene ring derived from resorcinol, which features a nitrile (–C≡N) group attached directly to the aromatic core. This central ring is connected via two ester linkages at the 1 and 3 positions to two identical extended side arms. Each arm consists of a benzoate moiety where the carbonyl carbon is bonded to the central ring's oxygen (Ar–O–C(=O)–Ar). The para position of this benzoate ring is linked through a second ester group (–C(=O)–O–) to a terminal phenyl ring. This terminal ring is substituted at the para position with a linear hexadecyl alkyl chain (–(CH2)15CH3). Consequently, the complete structure comprises a central aromatic ring flanked by two wings, each containing two additional benzene rings, multiple ester functional groups, and terminating in long C16 hydrocarbon tails.

A rod-like aromatic diester comprising three benzene rings connected linearly by ester linkages. The molecule features a nitro group on one terminal ring and two methoxy groups on the other terminal ring.

This compound is a linear, two-coordinate gold(I) complex featuring two distinct carbon-donor ligands. The first ligand is an alkynyl group derived from a biphenyl core; specifically, it consists of two phenyl rings connected by a single bond, with an ethynyl group attached at the para position of one ring and a propoxy group (–O–CH2–CH2–CH3) attached at the para position of the opposing ring. The ethynyl carbon is directly bonded to the gold center. The second ligand is 1-pentyl isocyanide, comprising a linear pentyl chain (–(CH2)4–CH3) attached to the nitrogen atom of an isocyanide group (R–N≡C). The terminal carbon of the isocyanide moiety coordinates to the gold atom, completing the linear C–Au–C coordination geometry.

Rod-like polysaccharide nanoparticles possessing the cellulose II crystal polymorph, characterized by antiparallel packing of glucan chains. The surface hydroxyl groups are partially functionalized with acetyl ester moieties, corresponding to a degree of substitution of 0.63.

phase_transition_behavior: Clearing point (T_NI/T_Iso) for 4-acetoxybenzoic acid is not reported in the provided TABLES or FIGURE CAPTIONS.
description: 4-Acetoxybenzoic acid consists of a benzene ring bearing two para-related substituents: a carboxylic acid group (–C(=O)OH) and an acetoxy group (–O–C(=O)CH3) formed by esterification of a phenolic oxygen. It can be synthesized by acetylating 4-hydroxybenzoic acid with acetic anhydride (commonly in an aromatic solvent such as toluene), converting the ring hydroxyl group into the acetate ester while retaining the benzoic acid functionality.
A lightweight ceramic network composed of silicon and carbon atoms, synthesized through carbothermal reduction or by reacting a carbon framework with silicon sources.
A molecular dye characterized by a perylene tetracarboxylic diimide core, N-substituted with branched 1-ethylpropyl chains to modulate solubility and packing.
A long-chain saturated wax ester synthesized via the esterification of octadecanoic acid and docosanol. It consists of a linear C18 acyl chain linked to a linear C22 alkyl chain.

A bis-azo compound consisting of a central phenyl ring connected to a terminal phenyl group and a terminal naphthalene group via two diazenyl bridges. This extended pi-conjugated system is investigated for its photoisomerization kinetics.
A protected nucleoside with a 5'-dimethoxytrityl group and a 2'-silyl ether, prepared as a precursor for oligonucleotide synthesis.

An electron-deficient small molecule semiconductor featuring an indeno[1,2-b]fluorene scaffold with dicyanovinylene acceptors and dodecyl-substituted thiophene donors. The 3-dodecylthiophene groups contain alkyl chains. It is prepared by palladium-catalyzed cross-coupling and subsequent condensation with malononitrile.
A disc-shaped molecule featuring a tristriazolotriazine core substituted with three 3,4,5-trihexyloxyphenyl groups.

An octahedral iron(II) coordination complex consisting of an iron(II) center coordinated by two tridentate 2,6-bis((dodecylimino)methyl)pyridine ligands, balanced by tetrafluoroborate counterions. The ligand structure is characterized by a central pyridine ring substituted at the 2 and 6 positions with (dodecylimino)methyl groups, featuring long dodecyl alkyl chains attached to the imine nitrogen atoms.
A gold(III) complex coordinated by a tridentate 2,6-bis(4-dodecyloxyphenyl)pyridine pincer ligand and a monodentate 4-(1H,1H,2H,2H-perfluorooctyloxy)phenylacetylide ligand.
A prenylated isoflavane originally isolated from licorice root. The structure features a complex fused tetracyclic system containing a pyran ring and two benzene rings.

phase_transition_behavior: From Table 2 (compound 13bs, heating): Cryst. → SmA → Iso. (clearing at 137.1 °C). Cooling shows: Iso. → SmA → SmC* → Cryst.
description: The compound is a 3,5-disubstituted 1,2,4-oxadiazole derivative. The oxadiazole ring is linked at the 3-position to a phenyl ring substituted at the para-position with a dodecyl ester group (dodecyl benzoate moiety). At the 5-position, the oxadiazole ring is attached to a biphenyl unit. The distal phenyl ring of this biphenyl system bears a para-substituent consisting of an ester linkage to a chiral 2-methyl-3-oxopropyl fragment, which terminates in an undecyl ester chain. The overall structure comprises a central 1,2,4-oxadiazole core flanked by a dodecyl benzoate group on one side and a biphenyl unit connected to a chiral undecyl ester-containing tail on the other.

An oligomeric hexamer is composed of six phenyl benzoate cores connected by heptamethylene linkers. The terminal ends of the molecule are capped with butoxy groups. This structure features alternating aromatic ester units and flexible alkyl chains.

A heteroaromatic azo compound consisting of an azulene-1-yl moiety connected via a diazenyl bridge to a 1,3,4-thiadiazole ring, which is substituted with a thiophen-2-yl group. It is synthesized by the diazotization of 1-aminoazulene followed by azo coupling with 2-amino-5-(thiophen-2-yl)-1,3,4-thiadiazole. This extended conjugated system acts as a functional monomer capable of electropolymerization to form redox-active films.

phase_transition_behavior: From Table 1 (compound 13ap): heating Cryst. → SmA (105.7 °C), SmA → Iso. (107.8 °C, not well resolved); cooling Iso. → SmA (105.3 °C), SmA → Cryst. (58.0 °C).
description: The molecule is built around a central 1,2,4-oxadiazole ring substituted at the 3- and 5-positions by para-substituted phenyl rings. The substituent at the 3-position is a phenyl ring bearing a para-positioned benzyl ester group (benzyl benzoate moiety). The substituent at the 5-position is a biphenyl unit attached via a para–para linkage. The distal phenyl ring of this biphenyl system carries a para-positioned ester linkage connecting to a chiral side chain. This side chain consists of a 2-methyl-3-oxypropionate fragment capped as an octyl ester (specifically, an octyl 3-hydroxy-2-methylpropanoate derivative linked via the hydroxyl oxygen).
An extended π-conjugated rod-like molecule containing a quinquethiophene central unit and terminal carbazole groups substituted with 3,4,5-tris(hexadecyloxy)benzyl moieties.

A pi-conjugated organic compound synthesized using Debus–Radziszewski methodology. The structure consists of a 1-methylimidazole core with 4-(dimethylamino)phenyl donors and a 4-cyanophenyl acceptor attached through a buta-1,3-dienyl bridge.
A six-membered ring containing two silicon atoms at the 1 and 4 positions, each substituted with a hydroxyl group and a methyl group in a trans configuration.

phase_transition_behavior: Not found in the provided TABLES or FIGURE CAPTIONS (no numeric clearing/transition data for 4-Cyano-4'-octylbiphenyl present there).
description: 4-Cyano-4'-octylbiphenyl is characterized by a biphenyl core, composed of two benzene rings linked by a single carbon–carbon bond. In this structure, one phenyl ring is substituted at the para position relative to the biaryl linkage with a linear n-octyl chain, while the opposing phenyl ring features a para-positioned nitrile group (–C≡N), establishing a linear aromatic–alkyl–nitrile connectivity.
A binary mixture composed of the zwitterionic viologen derivative 3-(1'-hexadecyl-4,4'-bipyridinium-1-yl)propane-1-sulfonate and bis(trifluoromethane)sulfonimide.
A star-shaped organic molecule featuring a tristriazolotriazine core substituted with three 3,4,5-tridecyloxyphenyl groups.
An indole heterocycle substituted with an electron-withdrawing nitrile group at the 4-position.

An alpha,beta-unsaturated ketone consisting of a phenyl group attached to a vinyl ketone moiety. It is synthesized via the trapping of formaldehyde with acetophenone and is obtained as a gummy liquid.
Layered CdS-CTAB nanocomposite
A semi-crystalline fluoropolymer produced from vinylidene difluoride.
A cationic poly(4-vinylpyridine) derivative with decyl side chains and a counterion denoted as In- (likely a pi-conjugated anion). It organizes into hexagonal nanodomains under humid conditions.
An allotrope of carbon consisting of sixty carbon atoms arranged in a spherical cage-like structure composed of fused pentagonal and hexagonal rings.

The molecule features a central symmetric squaramide core acting as a diamide unit. This core is connected via methylene bridges to two peripheral benzene rings. Each of these aromatic rings is substituted with three dodecyloxy chains, creating a bulky hydrophobic exterior surrounding the central polar hydrogen-bonding moiety.
An amino acid derivative synthesized from L-valine, featuring a 4-ethynylbenzoyl group at the N-terminus and a long alkyl decyl chain at the C-terminus.
A sphingomyelin in which the acyl group attached to the sphingosine backbone is specified as stearoyl.

A two-dimensional hybrid organic-inorganic perovskite prepared from hexylammonium iodide and lead(II) iodide. The structure features inorganic lead iodide sheets intercalated with hexylammonium cations.

c-DOPA(12) • KBF4 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A benzoxazole compound substituted at the 2-position with a phenol group, featuring an intramolecular hydrogen bond that facilitates excited-state proton transfer.

phase_transition_behavior: No clearing point or phase-sequence information is reported in the provided figure captions or any included tables (only references to Supporting Information tables are present without the tabulated values).
description:
N,N-Dimethyldodecylamine N-oxide consists of a straight twelve-carbon alkyl chain (dodecyl group) bonded to a tertiary amine oxide headgroup. The nitrogen is covalently attached to the dodecyl carbon and to two methyl substituents, and it bears a formal positive charge; the oxygen is singly bonded to nitrogen and bears a formal negative charge, giving the N→O (amine oxide) functionality without any rings or unsaturation.

A common synthetic route starts from N,N-dimethyldodecylamine, which is prepared by alkylation of dimethylamine with a dodecyl electrophile (such as a dodecyl halide) to form the tertiary amine. The tertiary amine is then oxidized at nitrogen using an oxidant (commonly hydrogen peroxide or a peracid) to install the N–O bond and produce the corresponding amine oxide.
A linear polymer formed from the reaction of decafluoroterphenyl with 1,12-dodecanediol. It contains alternating rigid fluorinated terphenyl units and flexible dodecamethylene chains.
The block copolymer contains crystalline PFOA domains within a macroscopic microphase-separated lamellar (LAM) structure.
A conjugated polymer based on a terthiophene backbone substituted with long tetradecyl side chains to influence molecular ordering and solubility.

phase_transition_behavior: Table 2 lists polymer II-Me (poly[oxy(decamethylcyclohexasiloxane-2,8-diyl)]) with an isotropization/clearing temperature Ti reported as a range: 200–230 °C (packing type noted as 1D).
description: Poly[oxy(decamethylcyclohexasiloxane-2,8-diyl)] is a cyclolinear polysiloxane composed of repeating decamethylcyclohexasiloxane units. The polymer backbone consists of six-membered siloxane rings, featuring alternating silicon and oxygen atoms, connected to one another through oxygen bridges (Si–O–Si linkages) at the 2 and 8 positions. Each silicon atom within the cyclic units is substituted with methyl groups. The structure is formed by the condensation of difunctional decamethylcyclohexasiloxane precursors, resulting in an alternating sequence of cyclic siloxane fragments linked by oxygen atoms.

A metallosurfactant salt consisting of a 1-dodecylpyridinium cation and a tetrachloroferrate(III) anion. Synthesized from the chloride precursor and iron(III) chloride, it forms yellow plate-like crystals arranged in interdigitated bilayers.

This supramolecular complex arises from the coordination of sodium iodide to the crown ether moiety of a dodecyl-substituted L-DOPA hybrid. The sodium cation is bound within the macrocyclic ether cavity. It features a lipophilic dodecyl chain attached to the amino acid core.

A polysaccharide-based nanostructure with rod-like morphology, characterized by a highly ordered crystalline arrangement of antiparallel polymer chains of N-acetylglucosamine. It possesses a high aspect ratio and surface functionalities including acetamide and hydroxyl groups that facilitate hydrogen bonding interactions.
A bio-based polymer derived from furan dicarboxylic acid and ethylene glycol.

A linear polyamide synthesized from 4,4'-oxydibenzoyl chloride and a diamine featuring a central bisphenol A linkage flanked by two azobenzene groups. The amorphous backbone contains extensive hydrogen-bonding sites and ether linkages.

The alpha-anomer of peracetylated glucopyranosyl azide, where the azide substituent occupies the axial position at the anomeric carbon. This stereochemical configuration allows it to participate in directional self-assembly processes similar to its beta-isomer.

An organic molecule featuring a 3-fluoro-4-nitrophenyl group at one terminus and a lateral pentyloxy chain. The core structure consists of three aromatic rings connected by carboxylate ester linkages.

This molecule features a central four-membered dione ring substituted with two symmetric nitrogen-bearing aryl groups. Each aromatic wing is decorated with three long dodecyl ether chains, creating a rod-like architecture with a rigid core and flexible periphery.
The molecule comprises two rigid aromatic segments connected by a flexible octamethylene spacer, with terminal glycidyl ether functional groups.

This compound is a boronic ester derivative obtained from the precursor BrPhC6BPC. The synthesis is achieved through a Miyaura borylation reaction. It is utilized as a structural coupling partner for the formation of an emitter core.
A symmetric molecule consisting of two 4'-cyanobiphenyl units linked at their 4-positions by a central heptyl chain.

A pi-shaped polyphilic block molecule featuring a p-terphenyl core with two lateral hexacosyloxy chains at the 2' and 3' positions and polar glycerol units at the 4 and 4'' positions. Synthesized via Suzuki cross-coupling of a 1,2-bis(hexacosyloxy)-3,6-diiodobenzene intermediate with a boronic acid derivative containing a protected glycerol moiety, followed by acidic deprotection.
A porous inorganic solid consisting of niobium and carbon, synthesized via a pseudomorphic transformation of a carbon aerogel template using niobium vapor.

phase_transition_behavior: No thermotropic clearing point (T_NI/T_Iso) is reported in the provided TABLES or FIGURE CAPTIONS for this lipopeptide; the text discusses concentration-dependent lyotropic ordering and gelation in aqueous buffer rather than a thermotropic isotropization transition.
description: N-palmitoyl-Trp-Gly-Gly-Arg-Gly-Asp-Ser is a lipopeptide characterized by a linear C16 hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) alkyl chain linked via an amide bond to the N-terminus of the heptapeptide sequence Trp–Gly–Gly–Arg–Gly–Asp–Ser. The peptide backbone consists of seven amino acid residues connected by standard amide linkages. Structurally, the tryptophan residue features an indole ring attached to the backbone via a methylene bridge. The arginine residue possesses a three-carbon aliphatic side chain ending in a guanidino group. The aspartic acid residue includes a side-chain carboxylic acid, while the serine residue presents a side-chain hydroxymethyl group. The molecule terminates at the C-terminus with a free carboxylic acid group.

A mannose derivative in which the anomeric carbon is linked via an alpha-glycosidic bond to a 4-aminophenyl group. The molecule possesses a hydrophilic sugar moiety and a reactive aromatic primary amine.

phase_transition_behavior: From Table 2, Polymer II-MePh (Me,Ph) shows an isotropization temperature (Ti) reported as 380–405 °C for the syndiotactic sample and 405–420 °C for the atactic sample; thus the clearing point (T_Iso) is up to 420 °C depending on tacticity.
description: The polymer consists of repeating cyclohexasiloxane units connected by siloxane linkages. Each repeating unit features a six-membered inorganic ring composed of alternating silicon and oxygen atoms. Two silicon atoms within the ring at the 2 and 8 positions are substituted with phenyl groups, while the remaining silicon atoms at the 4, 6, 10, and 12 positions are substituted with methyl groups, resulting in an octamethyl-substituted framework. The polymer backbone is formed by oxygen bridges linking the 2 and 8 positions of successive cyclohexasiloxane rings, creating an –O–(cyclohexasiloxane-2,8-diyl)–O– chain structure.

A polycyclic aromatic compound featuring a naphthalene core linked to a pentafluorophenyl group via a tetrafluoroethylene bridge. The structure allows for intramolecular pi-stacking interactions between the parallel aromatic rings.
A cyclic polyol and cyclohexane carboxylic acid derived from plant sources.
A diarylethene molecule noted for thermally irreversible photochromic reactions and rapid reversible shape changes in molecular crystals.

An amino acid derivative characterized by a catechol functional group on the phenyl ring. It serves as a key component in mussel adhesive proteins, facilitating strong bonding interactions in wet environments.
Chiral dopant synthesized from anti-2,2-difluoro-1,3-diphenyl-1,3-propanediol and 2,2-dimethoxypropane. Referred to as (R,R)-4.

An aromatic ester constructed from a 4-nitrophenyl 4-hydroxybenzoate scaffold and 2,4,6-trimethylbenzoic acid. The terminal aryl group is substituted with three methyl groups in a mesityl arrangement.

A cyclolinear polymer consisting of 1,4-dimethyl-1,4-disilacyclohexane rings connected by oxygen atoms, where the backbone comprises six-membered rings containing silicon atoms at the 1 and 4 positions.
A peracetylated guanosine derivative modified with a trifluoromethyl group at the 8-position. It is obtained via radical trifluoromethylation using zinc trifluoromethanesulfinate.

An oligomeric tetramer comprises four phenyl benzoate cores connected by heptamethylene spacers. The rigid aromatic units are linked in a linear fashion by these flexible alkyl chains. The molecule is terminated at both ends by butoxy groups.
A molecule consisting of a dodecyl alkyl chain attached via a glycosidic bond to a maltose disaccharide unit.

A star-shaped molecule featuring a central cyclotriphosphazene core substituted with six identical arms. Each arm consists of an extended aromatic structure linked via an imine (Schiff base) group, incorporating an amide linkage and terminating in a tetradecyloxy alkyl chain.
An oligomer featuring a 2,2'-bithiophene core flanked by two terminal carbazole units, where the nitrogen atom of each carbazole is substituted with a 3,4,5-tris(hexadecyloxy)benzyl group.

An asymmetric dicationic surfactant derived from hydrogenated cardanol. It is prepared by alkylating the phenol with 1,4-dibromobut-2-ene, followed by reaction with a butyl-substituted diazabicyclo[2.2.2]octane salt. It features a rigid bicyclic headgroup and a long hydrophobic tail.

A squaraine dye featuring a central four-membered squaric acid-derived ring flanked by two N,N-dimethylaniline groups. The molecule possesses a donor-acceptor-donor structure, leading to intense absorption in the visible region. It is used in organic photovoltaics and as a fluorescent probe.

phase_transition_behavior: Clearing point (T_NI/T_Iso) not found in the provided TABLES or FIG CAPTIONS for this compound.
description: 4-((Decylimino)methyl)-2-methoxyphenol consists of a substituted benzene ring bearing three key substituents: (1) a phenolic hydroxyl group directly bonded to the aromatic ring, (2) a methoxy group attached through an aryl–O bond (aryl–O–CH3), and (3) an imine (Schiff base) substituent where a ring-bound methine carbon is double-bonded to nitrogen (–CH=N–) and that nitrogen is single-bonded to a linear decyl chain (–(CH2)9CH3). It can be synthesized by forming the C=N linkage via condensation of the corresponding methoxy-hydroxy-substituted benzaldehyde (vanillin-type aromatic aldehyde) with decylamine, producing the aryl-aldimine connection between the aromatic –CH= fragment and the decyl-substituted imine nitrogen.

A partially deuterated organic molecule consisting of a biphenyl core with deuterium substitutions on the aromatic rings, substituted at the 4-position with a nitrile group and at the 4'-position with a protonated pentyl chain.

An octahedral iron(II) complex coordinated by two tridentate 2,6-bis((hexadecylimino)methyl)pyridine ligands, balanced by tetrafluoroborate counterions. The ligand structure features a central pyridine ring substituted at the 2 and 6 positions with imine groups, which are further attached to long hexadecyl aliphatic chains.

DPCE-ECh comprises an aromatic organic scaffold with a rigid core, linkers, and flexible side chains. The structure features heteroatom-containing groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

An aromatic ester compound comprising three benzene rings linked by ester groups, featuring a butoxy lateral chain, a methoxy group, and a fluorine substituent positioned ortho to a terminal nitro group.

A hexasubstituted cyclotriphosphazene compound featuring a central phosphazene ring connected via P-O bonds to six rigid side arms. Each arm consists of three aromatic rings linked by two Schiff base (imine) groups and terminates in a hydroxyl group.
An essential alpha-amino acid featuring an indole heterocycle attached to the backbone. It serves as a fundamental building block for proteins and a biological precursor for serotonin and niacin.

Tris(1-sec-butyl-3-tert-butyltriazenide)aluminum(III) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
The molecule consists of a central heptyl spacer connecting two 6-(4-cyanophenyl)naphthalen-2-yl sulfide groups.
An aromatic ester derivative composed of three benzene rings linked by ester groups, featuring a pentyl ether chain at the lateral position and terminating in a polar nitro moiety.

C10AzoC4E4 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers to flexible side chains. It contains heteroatom functional groups and extended conjugation. The substituent patterns and terminal groups modulate the steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A star-shaped molecule featuring a central tris([1,2,4]triazolo)[1,5-a:1',5'-c:1'',5''-e][1,3,5]triazine core substituted with three 3,5-didecyloxyphenyl groups.

phase_transition_behavior: From Table 1 (n = 7, CBS7OBO7SCB): heating phase sequence Cr 149.4 N 162.4 I. Cooling data show I 160.2 N; a monotropic NTB transition at 126 (POM) and crystallization at 130.0.
description: The molecule consists of a central 4,4′-biphenyl core symmetrically substituted at the 4 and 4′ positions. Extending from each of these positions is a heptyloxy spacer group (–O–(CH2)7–). Each heptyl chain is connected via a thioether linkage (–S–) to a terminal 4-cyanobiphenyl unit. Specifically, the sulfur atom links the end of the heptyl chain to the 4′-position of the terminal biphenyl, while the 4-position of that same terminal biphenyl bears a nitrile group (–C≡N). The overall structure comprises a central biphenyl unit flanked by two identical arms, each containing a seven-carbon alkoxy chain, a sulfur atom, and a terminal cyanobiphenyl moiety.
A furan-3-carboxylic acid derivative substituted with an unsaturated ester side chain. It is synthesized from 4-HMF derivatives and serves as a precursor for cross-linking copolymers.
An inorganic salt comprising a strontium cation and a carbonate anion, commonly synthesized by the reaction of a strontium salt with a soluble carbonate.
A supramolecular complex formed by the coordination of potassium hexafluorophosphate to the crown ether moiety of a hexadecyl-substituted tetrahydroisoquinoline hybrid.

A derivative of 2,2-dimethyl-1,3-propanediol featuring fully deuterated methyl groups attached to the central quaternary carbon. It serves to isolate the dynamic contributions of the methyl rotors in the solid state.
Dialkyl-substituted chiral thiophene monomer.
A thiazolo[5,4-d]thiazole derivative functionalized with dodecyl-substituted thiophene groups, utilized as an organic semiconductor in thin-film transistors.
